80
00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:28.040
I'm going to take all the
lessons that we've learned

81
00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:30.810
and try to walk you through
FlashAttention saying, see,

82
00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:32.210
here's how it all
comes together.

83
00:03:32.210 --> 00:03:36.560
So that's the last part
of today's lecture.

84
00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:41.160
So many of you have
taken an NLP course.

85
00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:42.610
And these days in
an NLP course, I

86
00:03:42.610 --> 00:03:44.730
think you teach some
amount of scaling laws.

87
00:03:44.730 --> 00:03:46.950
And so you've probably
seen this, right?

88
00:03:46.950 --> 00:03:49.520
And so this is just
setting the context.

89
00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:51.560
We know that having
more compute is

90
00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:54.030
helpful for training
large language models.

91
00:03:54.030 --> 00:03:55.770
This is a pre-training
scaling chart.

92
00:03:55.770 --> 00:03:58.187
But you could replace this
with an inference scaling chart

93
00:03:58.187 --> 00:03:59.110
if you would like.

94
00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:01.757
It's generally agreed upon
that the more compute you have,

95
00:04:01.757 --> 00:04:03.590
the more processing you
can do on your data.

96
00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:04.632
You can ingest more data.

97
00:04:04.632 --> 00:04:06.050
You can train larger models.

98
00:04:06.050 --> 00:04:07.970
All of those lead to
improved performance.

99
00:04:07.970 --> 00:04:11.067
So you might think of
course, deep learning

100
00:04:11.067 --> 00:04:11.900
is really important.

101
00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:13.480
But what's really
driven performance

102
00:04:13.480 --> 00:04:15.920
is faster hardware,
better utilization,

103
00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:17.000
improved parallelization.

104
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.860
So that's setting the
stage of why hardware

105
00:04:20.860 --> 00:04:22.960
is important to understand.

106
00:04:22.960 --> 00:04:25.910
And of course, once you think
about compute scaling you ask,

107
00:04:25.910 --> 00:04:27.470
OK, how do we get
compute scaling?

108
00:04:27.470 --> 00:04:30.650
How do we get our
models to train faster?

109
00:04:30.650 --> 00:04:35.230
So in the early days, of
semiconductor scaling,

110
00:04:35.230 --> 00:04:37.700
if you were thinking
about, OK, CPUs,

111
00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:41.622
how do they get faster, they
would scale under something

112
00:04:41.622 --> 00:04:42.580
called Dennard scaling.

113
00:04:42.580 --> 00:04:46.600
With Moore's law, you would
double the amount of transistors

114
00:04:46.600 --> 00:04:48.430
on a chip every year.

115
00:04:48.430 --> 00:04:50.380
And if you have this
doubling, what you end up

116
00:04:50.380 --> 00:04:54.610
is Dennard scaling where smaller
and smaller transistors can

117
00:04:54.610 --> 00:04:56.560
be driven at faster
and faster clock speeds

118
00:04:56.560 --> 00:04:58.960
with lower and lower power,
which in turn give you

119
00:04:58.960 --> 00:04:59.720
more performance.

120
00:04:59.720 --> 00:05:03.650
And then in the 1980s to
2000, this tapped out.

121
00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:06.430
You can see in this chart
here by Hennessy and Patterson

122
00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:09.310
that single thread performance,
that's the blue dots here,

123
00:05:09.310 --> 00:05:10.930
that basically
started to taper out.

124
00:05:10.930 --> 00:05:12.430
Of course, the
number of transistors

125
00:05:12.430 --> 00:05:14.720
didn't really start falling off.

126
00:05:14.720 --> 00:05:17.620
You did have chips with higher
and higher transistor densities.

127
00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:18.620
But that wasn't helpful.

128
00:05:18.620 --> 00:05:22.480
It wasn't giving you higher
throughput on single threads.

129
00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:26.290
And so, this means that we
can't just do computation faster

130
00:05:26.290 --> 00:05:27.820
in absolute terms.

131
00:05:27.820 --> 00:05:31.820
What we have to make up for
it with is parallel scaling.

132
00:05:31.820 --> 00:05:35.860
So the story of scaling for deep
learning and neural networks

133
00:05:35.860 --> 00:05:38.710
is going from single-thread
scaling, which is just

134
00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:41.560
doing your computation
faster in absolute terms,

135
00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:44.320
to parallel scaling where
you have a lot of workloads

136
00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.420
that are all computed at once.

137
00:05:46.420 --> 00:05:50.140
And this is one of my
favorite compute scaling

138
00:05:50.140 --> 00:05:52.600
charts by Bill Dally
and his keynote

139
00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:55.410
where he's showing the
super exponential increase

140
00:05:55.410 --> 00:05:59.760
in the number of integer
operations per second,

141
00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:04.090
going from the earliest
K20's to the H100.

142
00:06:04.090 --> 00:06:08.310
And it's this really
remarkable exponential

143
00:06:08.310 --> 00:06:10.050
or super exponential curve.

144
00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:12.660
And so we have to
really understand

145
00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:15.150
how to take advantage
of this curve

146
00:06:15.150 --> 00:06:18.540
in order to really get the
most out of our language model.

147
00:06:18.540 --> 00:06:22.710
So that's kind of
going to be our goal.

148
00:06:22.710 --> 00:06:24.600
And so I've already
hinted at this kind

149
00:06:24.600 --> 00:06:26.110
of important difference, right?

150
00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:28.320
CPU is something
that I think everyone

151
00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:30.850
is familiar with once you
start doing programming.

152
00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:32.440
It's this execution model.

153
00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:34.123
If you have a program,
it goes through.

154
00:06:34.123 --> 00:06:35.790
And in a single thread,
it executes step

155
00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:37.060
by step what's happening.

156
00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:40.200
And in order to support that
kind of an execution model, what

157
00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:40.720
do you need?

158
00:06:40.720 --> 00:06:42.640
Well, you need
big control units.

159
00:06:42.640 --> 00:06:45.552
You just need to generally
run these things very quickly

160
00:06:45.552 --> 00:06:47.010
because you have
a lot of branching

161
00:06:47.010 --> 00:06:49.360
and you have a lot of
conditional control logic.

162
00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:52.320
So a CPU-- this is an
abstracted diagram--

163
00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:56.010
is going to dedicate
a lot of its chip

164
00:06:56.010 --> 00:06:58.780
towards large control
branch prediction.

165
00:06:58.780 --> 00:07:01.200
And it's going to run these
very quickly because it

166
00:07:01.200 --> 00:07:02.770
doesn't have that many threads.

167
00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:05.260
There are CPUs with lots
and lots of cores now.

168
00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:07.920
But compared to a GPU
it's almost nothing.

169
00:07:07.920 --> 00:07:12.870
And so in contrast, the GPU
has really tons and tons

170
00:07:12.870 --> 00:07:14.710
of compute units ALUs.

171
00:07:14.710 --> 00:07:16.600
So those are the
little green boxes.

172
00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:19.560
And there's much smaller
amounts of the chip dedicated

173
00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:20.230
to control.

174
00:07:20.230 --> 00:07:23.100
So there's a little bit of
control logic orchestrating

175
00:07:23.100 --> 00:07:28.170
tons and tons of compute
units operating in parallel.

176
00:07:28.170 --> 00:07:29.760
And I think
mentally-- so this is

177
00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:32.430
the picture of what
is being emphasized

178
00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:34.330
in a CPU versus a GPU.

179
00:07:34.330 --> 00:07:36.720
But if you look at what's
the design goals are,

180
00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:40.090
they designed for
very different goals.

181
00:07:40.090 --> 00:07:43.210
So you can think about CPUs
as optimizing for latency.

182
00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:45.640
I want to finish my tasks
as quickly as possible.

183
00:07:45.640 --> 00:07:50.830
So if I have tasks T1 through
T4 here on the right side,

184
00:07:50.830 --> 00:07:53.590
in a CPU, I'm going to
try to finish each task as

185
00:07:53.590 --> 00:07:54.620
quickly as possible.

186
00:07:54.620 --> 00:07:56.692
And so if you want
any one of these tasks

187
00:07:56.692 --> 00:07:58.150
to be finished
quickly, T1 is going

188
00:07:58.150 --> 00:07:59.720
to complete really quickly.

189
00:07:59.720 --> 00:08:02.690
In GPU, you're optimizing
for high throughput.

190
00:08:02.690 --> 00:08:05.650
I don't care about latency,
I just want all of my tasks

191
00:08:05.650 --> 00:08:08.410
that I have in aggregate, to
complete as quickly as possible.

192
00:08:08.410 --> 00:08:10.930
And to support that, maybe
you have lots of threads

193
00:08:10.930 --> 00:08:13.840
and these threads can go to
sleep and wake up very quickly.

194
00:08:13.840 --> 00:08:16.780
And in the end, you finish
all of your workload T1

195
00:08:16.780 --> 00:08:20.540
through T4 before
the CPU 1 does,

196
00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:23.290
even though individually all
of these have higher latency.

197
00:08:23.290 --> 00:08:28.690
So they have different design
principles and design goals.

198
00:08:28.690 --> 00:08:29.950
OK.

199
00:08:29.950 --> 00:08:33.620
And so a GPU has a
pretty different anatomy.

200
00:08:33.620 --> 00:08:38.108
And I don't know if you all have
ever looked at what a GPU layout

201
00:08:38.108 --> 00:08:38.900
diagram looks like.

202
00:08:38.900 --> 00:08:43.150
I'll actually show you the
chip figures in a moment here.

203
00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:46.960
But the core idea, and this is
important conceptual concepts

204
00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:53.820
behind a GPU, is that a GPU
executes many, many SM streaming

205
00:08:53.820 --> 00:08:54.810
multiprocessors.

206
00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:56.580
And a streaming
multiprocessor you

207
00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:58.688
can think of as an atomic unit.

208
00:08:58.688 --> 00:09:00.730
When you're programming
in something like Triton,

209
00:09:00.730 --> 00:09:03.460
they're going to operate
at the level of an SM.

210
00:09:03.460 --> 00:09:06.030
And within each SM,
they're going to--

211
00:09:06.030 --> 00:09:09.220
it contains many SPs,
Streaming Processors,

212
00:09:09.220 --> 00:09:11.730
and a streaming
processor is going

213
00:09:11.730 --> 00:09:14.970
to execute a whole bunch
of threads in parallel.

214
00:09:14.970 --> 00:09:18.490
So one way to think about it is
SM has a bunch of control logic.

215
00:09:18.490 --> 00:09:19.840
It can decide what to execute.

216
00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:21.570
It can do for
example, branching.

217
00:09:21.570 --> 00:09:25.500
SPs are going to operate--
to take the same instruction

218
00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:27.850
and apply it to many
different pieces of data.

219
00:09:27.850 --> 00:09:31.770
And so you can do tons and
tons of parallel computation.

220
00:09:31.770 --> 00:09:35.440
Under this model, an SM is
each granular unit of control.

221
00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:38.260
SP can do a lot of
computation individually.

222
00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:40.980
And if you look at an A100,
which is the previous generation

223
00:09:40.980 --> 00:09:44.520
GPU, at this point
you've got 128 SMS.

224
00:09:44.520 --> 00:09:47.440
That's a lot more than
most cores for CPUs.

225
00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:48.860
And each of these
systems is going

226
00:09:48.860 --> 00:09:51.530
to have a very
large number of SPs

227
00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:54.910
and specialized matrix
multiply units inside them.

228
00:09:58.679 --> 00:10:00.775
And so that's kind
of the compute model.

229
00:10:00.775 --> 00:10:01.650
Was there a question?

230
00:10:01.650 --> 00:10:02.150
Sorry.

231
00:10:02.150 --> 00:10:02.785
Yeah.

232
00:10:02.785 --> 00:10:08.540
[INAUDIBLE] back to the other
slide before Anatomy of GPUs.

233
00:10:08.540 --> 00:10:11.460
So is this GPU the
same as that GPU?

234
00:10:11.460 --> 00:10:13.710
So the question was, is this
GPU the same as that GPU?

235
00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:14.210
Yes.

236
00:10:14.210 --> 00:10:17.400
Like this is a kind of
cartoon version of this.

237
00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:19.770
You can think of each
row as being an SM.

238
00:10:19.770 --> 00:10:22.250
It's got its own control
units, and each green block

239
00:10:22.250 --> 00:10:24.480
might be one of these
green blocks here,

240
00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:28.020
like a FP32 processing
unit inside of it.

241
00:10:28.020 --> 00:10:31.520
And each SM can
operate various pieces

242
00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:37.070
that it owns, like the tensor
cores to do computation.

243
00:10:37.070 --> 00:10:39.410
Cool.

244
00:10:39.410 --> 00:10:40.170
OK.

245
00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:43.410
And there's going to be
two important things.

246
00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:45.330
You think of GPUs as computers.

247
00:10:45.330 --> 00:10:45.920
They compute.

248
00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:49.090
But actually computation is only
one of the two important things

249
00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:50.260
we have to keep track of.

250
00:10:50.260 --> 00:10:53.510
Memory is arguably more
important, at this point,

251
00:10:53.510 --> 00:10:55.690
and it will continue to
be more important in terms

252
00:10:55.690 --> 00:10:57.430
of the performance
profiles of how

253
00:10:57.430 --> 00:10:59.920
we run our programs on the GPU.

254
00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:01.840
And so to understand
memory, you have

255
00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:04.700
to understand the physical
layout of the GPU and the chip,

256
00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:06.610
because in some
sense, when you're

257
00:11:06.610 --> 00:11:10.210
operating at such fast
speeds, the physical proximity

258
00:11:10.210 --> 00:11:12.200
of the memory starts
to matter quite a bit.

259
00:11:12.200 --> 00:11:14.080
And so I will show you
the physical proximity

260
00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:15.580
of how things are
laid out and how

261
00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:18.400
that relates to how you should
think about memory access

262
00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:19.670
and performance.

263
00:11:19.670 --> 00:11:23.950
So the closer a piece
of memory is to each SM,

264
00:11:23.950 --> 00:11:25.400
the faster it's going to be.

265
00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:28.450
So there's going to be certain
very, very, very fast kinds

266
00:11:28.450 --> 00:11:30.890
of memory, like L1
and shared memory,

267
00:11:30.890 --> 00:11:33.910
and that's going to
live inside of the SM.

268
00:11:33.910 --> 00:11:35.410
And that's going
to be really fast.

269
00:11:35.410 --> 00:11:37.870
Things like registers, things
you're reading and writing

270
00:11:37.870 --> 00:11:39.730
very frequently, you're
going to want to put

271
00:11:39.730 --> 00:11:41.950
into the L1 and shared memory.

272
00:11:41.950 --> 00:11:44.710
L2 cache, as you
can see, there's

273
00:11:44.710 --> 00:11:46.720
these green areas which are SMs.

274
00:11:46.720 --> 00:11:48.340
And then there's
these blue areas.

275
00:11:48.340 --> 00:11:50.070
This is on the GPU chip.

276
00:11:50.070 --> 00:11:53.980
These are L2 memory that's
right next to the SMs.

277
00:11:53.980 --> 00:11:55.920
So they're not inside
the SMs, but they're

278
00:11:55.920 --> 00:11:57.400
physically still quite close.

279
00:11:57.400 --> 00:12:00.720
And these are still pretty fast.

280
00:12:00.720 --> 00:12:04.600
They're still a
factor of 10 slower,

281
00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:06.190
but they're still
reasonably fast.

282
00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:10.050
And then outside of
the chip itself, I

283
00:12:10.050 --> 00:12:12.930
think this is like a 3090 card
or something like this, or maybe

284
00:12:12.930 --> 00:12:14.200
a PCIe A100.

285
00:12:14.200 --> 00:12:15.960
Oh, this is a PCIe A100.

286
00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:18.570
You've got your GPU here,
and you've got actually

287
00:12:18.570 --> 00:12:21.810
DRAM living next to the chip.

288
00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:24.780
So it has to actually go
physically outside of the chip

289
00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:25.510
and connect.

290
00:12:25.510 --> 00:12:27.840
And you can see on
this chip diagram

291
00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:30.130
here these yellow
connectors at the edges.

292
00:12:30.130 --> 00:12:31.870
These are HBM connectors.

293
00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:35.400
These are connecting
to the DRAM chips that

294
00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:38.410
are outside of the actual GPU.

295
00:12:38.410 --> 00:12:42.370
And you can see the speed that
it takes to access these, right?

296
00:12:42.370 --> 00:12:45.110
The on SM memory is
much, much faster,

297
00:12:45.110 --> 00:12:48.103
like 20 clock cycles to
access something from there,

298
00:12:48.103 --> 00:12:50.520
whereas it's going to take
something like 200 or 300 clock

299
00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:54.040
cycles to access something from
the L2 cache or global memory.

300
00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:56.710
And this factor of 10 is
going to hurt you real bad.

301
00:12:56.710 --> 00:13:00.030
So if you have a
piece of computation

302
00:13:00.030 --> 00:13:03.115
that requires you to
access global memory,

303
00:13:03.115 --> 00:13:04.740
it might mean that
you actually run out

304
00:13:04.740 --> 00:13:05.950
of work to do on your SM.

305
00:13:05.950 --> 00:13:07.110
You've multiplied
all the matrices.

306
00:13:07.110 --> 00:13:07.840
You've run out.

307
00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:09.105
Now you just have to idle.

308
00:13:09.105 --> 00:13:10.480
So you utilization
won't be good.

309
00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:12.360
And this will be a really
key theme, thinking

310
00:13:12.360 --> 00:13:13.900
about memories in some sense.

311
00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:17.880
The key to thinking
about how GPUs work.

312
00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:19.590
And in assignment
two, you're going

313
00:13:19.590 --> 00:13:24.190
to actually be writing high
performance code for a GPU.

314
00:13:24.190 --> 00:13:27.150
So you have to actually think
about the execution model of how

315
00:13:27.150 --> 00:13:29.940
a GPU actually executes things.

316
00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:33.330
And this is somewhat
complicated, but not insanely

317
00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:34.530
so.

318
00:13:34.530 --> 00:13:37.440
There's three
granularities of things

319
00:13:37.440 --> 00:13:38.800
that you need to think about.

320
00:13:38.800 --> 00:13:42.100
There's blocks, there's
warps, and there's threads,

321
00:13:42.100 --> 00:13:45.410
and that's the order in which
the granularity narrows down.

322
00:13:45.410 --> 00:13:48.840
Blocks are these big
groups of threads.

323
00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:52.110
And each block is going
to be assigned to a SM.

324
00:13:52.110 --> 00:13:54.660
So think about this as each
SM is kind of a worker.

325
00:13:54.660 --> 00:13:56.220
It's its own autonomous unit.

326
00:13:56.220 --> 00:13:59.850
And a block is going to be
assigned to an SM to process.

327
00:13:59.850 --> 00:14:01.590
So this is each granular unit.

328
00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:05.220
Now then within these blocks
are a whole bunch of threads.

329
00:14:05.220 --> 00:14:08.570
Each thread is a piece of
task that needs to be done.

330
00:14:08.570 --> 00:14:10.580
And when these threads
execute, they're

331
00:14:10.580 --> 00:14:12.360
going to execute in groups.

332
00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:13.950
And this is a thing
called a warp.

333
00:14:13.950 --> 00:14:16.710
So you take a block which
is a collection of threads.

334
00:14:16.710 --> 00:14:19.740
And you're going to take
threads from that block,

335
00:14:19.740 --> 00:14:21.710
and they're going to
execute in groups of 32

336
00:14:21.710 --> 00:14:24.000
consecutively numbered
threads each time.

337
00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:25.590
And that's of called warps.

338
00:14:25.590 --> 00:14:28.560
And so you can see at this
diagram here what's happening.

339
00:14:28.560 --> 00:14:29.880
You've got a bunch of blocks.

340
00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:31.910
Each block is assigned
to a different SM.

341
00:14:31.910 --> 00:14:33.410
And within each
block, there's going

342
00:14:33.410 --> 00:14:34.950
to be many different warps.

343
00:14:34.950 --> 00:14:36.830
And each warp is
going to consist

344
00:14:36.830 --> 00:14:38.610
of a whole bunch of threads.

345
00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:40.340
And all of these
threads are going

346
00:14:40.340 --> 00:14:43.680
to execute the same
instruction on different data.

347
00:14:43.680 --> 00:14:45.740
And so this is kind of
the execution model.

348
00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:48.600
Right now it's going to it
seems probably mysterious.

349
00:14:48.600 --> 00:14:50.490
What these blocks, and
warps and threads are.

350
00:14:50.490 --> 00:14:52.280
They will have
important implications

351
00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:57.090
for performance in how we design
things like CUDA kernels later.

352
00:14:57.090 --> 00:14:58.590
So hopefully you
can remember this.

353
00:14:58.590 --> 00:15:01.880
I'll refresh your
memory as we go.

354
00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:04.400
Hopefully, that's clear.

355
00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:08.392
So that was the kind of logical
execution model of a GPU.

356
00:15:08.392 --> 00:15:10.100
And if you understand
that you understand

357
00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:12.440
how GPUs execute things.

358
00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:15.478
There's also a logical
memory model of a GPU.

359
00:15:15.478 --> 00:15:17.520
So now I'm not showing
you the physical hardware.

360
00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:21.030
This is just how you think
about the programming of a GPU.

361
00:15:21.030 --> 00:15:22.980
And so there's registers.

362
00:15:22.980 --> 00:15:25.040
So these are really
fast, storing

363
00:15:25.040 --> 00:15:26.580
single numbers type storage.

364
00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:29.060
You've got local memory,
you've got shared memory,

365
00:15:29.060 --> 00:15:30.510
and you've got global memory.

366
00:15:30.510 --> 00:15:34.650
And that increases in
the memory hierarchy.

367
00:15:34.650 --> 00:15:36.860
You get slower and
slower and slower.

368
00:15:36.860 --> 00:15:39.257
And your code can
write to global memory.

369
00:15:39.257 --> 00:15:40.840
It can also write
the constant memory,

370
00:15:40.840 --> 00:15:44.070
which is not something
that's used too often.

371
00:15:44.070 --> 00:15:47.250
And so each thread can
access its own register

372
00:15:47.250 --> 00:15:48.340
and shared memory.

373
00:15:48.340 --> 00:15:50.500
But information that
goes across blocks

374
00:15:50.500 --> 00:15:52.000
need to be written
to global memory.

375
00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:53.542
And this is actually
quite important.

376
00:15:53.542 --> 00:15:57.360
So now it means that whenever
you write a thread that

377
00:15:57.360 --> 00:15:59.550
executes something,
ideally it's operating

378
00:15:59.550 --> 00:16:02.075
on the same small
amount of data.

379
00:16:02.075 --> 00:16:04.450
So you load that small amount
of data into shared memory.

380
00:16:04.450 --> 00:16:07.120
All the threads are very happy
accessing that shared memory.

381
00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:07.990
It terminates.

382
00:16:07.990 --> 00:16:08.830
It's done.

383
00:16:08.830 --> 00:16:10.450
That would be a great
execution model.

384
00:16:10.450 --> 00:16:11.867
Instead, if you
have a thread that

385
00:16:11.867 --> 00:16:14.100
needs to access data all
over the place, that's

386
00:16:14.100 --> 00:16:16.870
going to have to access global
memory, that's very, very slow.

387
00:16:16.870 --> 00:16:19.590
This theme will come back as
we talk about different ways

388
00:16:19.590 --> 00:16:22.920
of operating on a GPU.

389
00:16:22.920 --> 00:16:24.330
Hopefully that's clear.

390
00:16:24.330 --> 00:16:27.000
That's kind of the
very high level,

391
00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.380
four-slide overview of a GPU.

392
00:16:29.380 --> 00:16:31.630
If you have questions about
how any of that works,

393
00:16:31.630 --> 00:16:35.460
feel free to ask me as I go on.

394
00:16:35.460 --> 00:16:38.390
OK, so here's a side thread.

395
00:16:38.390 --> 00:16:40.100
Last year I didn't
cover this because I

396
00:16:40.100 --> 00:16:42.980
think resources on
TPUs was a little thin,

397
00:16:42.980 --> 00:16:45.380
but the nice TPU
book or internet

398
00:16:45.380 --> 00:16:48.740
website that I mentioned at the
start of the lecture came out,

399
00:16:48.740 --> 00:16:50.730
and that has actually
a lot of nice details.

400
00:16:50.730 --> 00:16:53.570
And I talked to a few
Google people about the TPU.

401
00:16:53.570 --> 00:16:56.790
And at a high level, it's
very, very similar to a GPU.

402
00:16:56.790 --> 00:16:59.700
And so I want to just talk
for a moment about TPUs.

403
00:16:59.700 --> 00:17:02.150
You may never operate
on a TPU, but I

404
00:17:02.150 --> 00:17:03.740
think it's important
to understand

405
00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:05.930
that these alternative
accelerators operate

406
00:17:05.930 --> 00:17:09.079
in many ways, very similarly.

407
00:17:09.079 --> 00:17:12.319
So here's a diagram of
what a TPU looks like.

408
00:17:12.319 --> 00:17:15.420
There's kind of a-- so there's
something called a tensor core.

409
00:17:15.420 --> 00:17:17.359
And mentally you can
think about a tensor core

410
00:17:17.359 --> 00:17:19.770
as being similar to an SM
or streaming multiprocessor.

411
00:17:19.770 --> 00:17:22.040
Each of these are kind
of its own atomic units

412
00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:23.730
that can operate on data.

413
00:17:23.730 --> 00:17:26.730
There's a scalar unit which
is basically a control unit.

414
00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:29.730
And it can also do
CPU-like arbitrary things.

415
00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:32.005
You've got a vector unit
that can operate on vectors.

416
00:17:32.005 --> 00:17:33.380
So if you've got
a vector and you

417
00:17:33.380 --> 00:17:36.120
want to operate entrywise on it,
that's a good place to do it.

418
00:17:36.120 --> 00:17:38.890
And then it's got a very
big specialized part

419
00:17:38.890 --> 00:17:41.630
of the chip dedicated to
just doing matrix multiply.

420
00:17:41.630 --> 00:17:43.180
It's called the MXU.

421
00:17:43.180 --> 00:17:46.790
And then it's got very fast
memory for vector memory and SM.

422
00:17:46.790 --> 00:17:50.627
Both of these are very fast on
chip or on tensor core memory.

423
00:17:50.627 --> 00:17:52.210
And then there's
high bandwidth memory

424
00:17:52.210 --> 00:17:53.840
that lives outside of the chip.

425
00:17:53.840 --> 00:17:56.420
So hopefully you see the
similarities to an SM.

426
00:17:56.420 --> 00:17:59.210
There's slow memory outside
very fast memory inside.

427
00:17:59.210 --> 00:18:02.740
And there's specialized hardware
to do matrix multiplication.

428
00:18:02.740 --> 00:18:05.020
The core structure is
very much the same.

429
00:18:05.020 --> 00:18:07.720
The difference is I'll talk
about this in the parallelism

430
00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:08.748
lecture next week.

431
00:18:08.748 --> 00:18:10.540
How the accelerators
are networked together

432
00:18:10.540 --> 00:18:12.070
is a little bit different.

433
00:18:12.070 --> 00:18:14.483
And then also mention
I didn't notice

434
00:18:14.483 --> 00:18:16.150
I didn't talk about
warps, I didn't talk

435
00:18:16.150 --> 00:18:18.040
about any of that other stuff.

436
00:18:18.040 --> 00:18:19.600
Tensor cores are
in some ways very

437
00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:23.290
simple because they're optimized
to just do matrix multiplies.

438
00:18:23.290 --> 00:18:25.720
The tensor core, unlike
the GPU, doesn't attempt

439
00:18:25.720 --> 00:18:26.900
to do anything but that.

440
00:18:26.900 --> 00:18:29.210
And so in some ways
very, very simple,

441
00:18:29.210 --> 00:18:32.020
much simpler in architecture,
but conceptually

442
00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:35.010
doing the same thing.

443
00:18:35.010 --> 00:18:37.320
Yes.

444
00:18:37.320 --> 00:18:40.320
Is it called tensor
because it's also

445
00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:43.530
in some ways optimized to
operate on general tensors

446
00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:47.010
or this is just enough
to work on [INAUDIBLE]?

447
00:18:47.010 --> 00:18:47.590
Yeah.

448
00:18:47.590 --> 00:18:49.320
So the question was
is it called tensor

449
00:18:49.320 --> 00:18:52.230
because it can operate
on arbitrary tensors.

450
00:18:52.230 --> 00:18:55.120
So it can operate on
arbitrary tensors.

451
00:18:55.120 --> 00:18:56.380
I can do the indexing.

452
00:18:56.380 --> 00:18:59.175
The operations that MXU
performs is a matrix multiply.

453
00:18:59.175 --> 00:19:01.050
And so it would always
be like a batch matrix

454
00:19:01.050 --> 00:19:02.920
multiply operating on a tensor.

455
00:19:02.920 --> 00:19:05.863
So it's kind of both a Yes and a
no answer, if that makes sense.

456
00:19:05.863 --> 00:19:08.280
So they operate on tensors,
but the operations they always

457
00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:10.740
perform are matrix multiply,
is not more complicated

458
00:19:10.740 --> 00:19:14.070
tensor operations
that you can do.

459
00:19:14.070 --> 00:19:15.630
Cool.

460
00:19:15.630 --> 00:19:18.840
The reason why the GPU
has been so successful

461
00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:21.400
is that it scales
up really easily.

462
00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:24.678
If you want more processing
power, just add more SMs.

463
00:19:24.678 --> 00:19:26.220
You don't have to
worry about driving

464
00:19:26.220 --> 00:19:29.580
the clock faster and getting
more heat dissipation problems.

465
00:19:29.580 --> 00:19:32.380
Programming-wise,
CUDA is intimidating,

466
00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:35.960
but it's actually not as
horrendous to program because

467
00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:37.310
of its programming model.

468
00:19:37.310 --> 00:19:39.960
Like, the way it works
is within each SM right,

469
00:19:39.960 --> 00:19:42.650
you have a thread, and it
executes the same instruction

470
00:19:42.650 --> 00:19:44.450
on a bunch of different
pieces of data.

471
00:19:44.450 --> 00:19:46.357
That's conceptually
easy to reason about.

472
00:19:46.357 --> 00:19:47.940
You can think through
what that means.

473
00:19:47.940 --> 00:19:50.240
And especially it's nice if
you're operating over a matrix

474
00:19:50.240 --> 00:19:52.020
and you're doing very
simple operations.

475
00:19:52.020 --> 00:19:54.650
It's exactly this
kind of simple model.

476
00:19:54.650 --> 00:19:57.330
Finally, each of these
threads are very lightweight,

477
00:19:57.330 --> 00:19:59.730
and they can be kind of stopped
and started at any time.

478
00:19:59.730 --> 00:20:01.970
And so if you need to
wait for another thread

479
00:20:01.970 --> 00:20:04.460
or if you need to evict
something and start

480
00:20:04.460 --> 00:20:06.838
another process, all these
threads are very lightweight.

481
00:20:06.838 --> 00:20:08.630
So this just kind of
means that there's not

482
00:20:08.630 --> 00:20:10.350
much state associated
with the threads,

483
00:20:10.350 --> 00:20:11.850
and they can be
stopped and started,

484
00:20:11.850 --> 00:20:16.420
which allows GPUs to get high
utilization within each SM.

485
00:20:19.310 --> 00:20:23.630
So GPUs, obviously
graphics processing units.

486
00:20:23.630 --> 00:20:26.430
And for much of its
life, in the early days,

487
00:20:26.430 --> 00:20:29.390
it was not used to do
scientific computing.

488
00:20:29.390 --> 00:20:32.790
But people-- because
it was programmable,

489
00:20:32.790 --> 00:20:37.060
researchers figured out how
to use early NVIDIA GPUs to do

490
00:20:37.060 --> 00:20:38.680
fast matrix multiplies.

491
00:20:38.680 --> 00:20:42.670
This is one of the early papers
on doing fast matrix multiplies

492
00:20:42.670 --> 00:20:44.860
with graphics
hardware, and it shows

493
00:20:44.860 --> 00:20:47.480
how you can hack kind of
things like the texture buffer.

494
00:20:47.480 --> 00:20:50.210
And so on to get it to
do matrix multiplies.

495
00:20:50.210 --> 00:20:53.590
And so even without specific
support for matmuls,

496
00:20:53.590 --> 00:20:56.260
researchers figured
out how to do it.

497
00:20:56.260 --> 00:20:59.870
But I think now, especially
in this day and age,

498
00:20:59.870 --> 00:21:02.690
NVIDIA and others have realized
matrix multiplies are special.

499
00:21:02.690 --> 00:21:05.560
If you're doing deep learning,
most of your workload

500
00:21:05.560 --> 00:21:06.920
is matrix multiplies.

501
00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:10.580
And so matrix multiplies are in
some sense blessed operations.

502
00:21:10.580 --> 00:21:14.890
So this is a chart showing the
number of teraFLOPs per second

503
00:21:14.890 --> 00:21:17.450
by different generations
of NVIDIA GPUs.

504
00:21:17.450 --> 00:21:20.000
And the orange line
is your matmul FLOPs,

505
00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.310
your performance you can
get if you're doing matmuls.

506
00:21:22.310 --> 00:21:25.240
The blue line is your
non-matmul FLOPs.

507
00:21:25.240 --> 00:21:27.850
And you see this
big, big gap at V100s

508
00:21:27.850 --> 00:21:31.540
when they started putting
in tensor cores that

509
00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:35.100
were specialized hardware
to do matrix multiplies.

510
00:21:35.100 --> 00:21:38.600
And you see this gigantic gap in
the matrix multiply performance

511
00:21:38.600 --> 00:21:40.680
relative to the
non-maximal performance.

512
00:21:40.680 --> 00:21:44.820
And so if you're going to design
any a neural architecture,

513
00:21:44.820 --> 00:21:47.310
I was saying this in the
architecture part as well.

514
00:21:47.310 --> 00:21:50.600
You have to have most of your
workload be matrix multiplies

515
00:21:50.600 --> 00:21:52.940
because that's the thing
that's orders of magnitude

516
00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:55.220
faster than any other
operation that you're going

517
00:21:55.220 --> 00:21:57.360
to be able to do on a GPU.

518
00:21:57.360 --> 00:22:00.480
So if you make like a
non-matmul-based neural network,

519
00:22:00.480 --> 00:22:03.140
you're going to be in
a big, big trouble.

520
00:22:03.140 --> 00:22:05.570
And then kind of the
last thing that I

521
00:22:05.570 --> 00:22:08.960
want you to understand
as just general facts.

522
00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:11.040
Matmuls is fast is one thing.

523
00:22:11.040 --> 00:22:13.130
But the other thing that's
important to remember

524
00:22:13.130 --> 00:22:16.100
is kind of the relative scaling
of the different components

525
00:22:16.100 --> 00:22:17.040
of the GPU.

526
00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:19.790
So this is a very nice
chart that shows you

527
00:22:19.790 --> 00:22:23.838
how quickly different
components of the GPU

528
00:22:23.838 --> 00:22:25.880
or different components
of the let's call it like

529
00:22:25.880 --> 00:22:28.140
LLM training stack are scaling.

530
00:22:28.140 --> 00:22:31.710
So the blue line
is the connectivity

531
00:22:31.710 --> 00:22:34.320
from the GPU to the host.

532
00:22:34.320 --> 00:22:36.460
The server that
it's attached to.

533
00:22:36.460 --> 00:22:39.520
So you can use PCIe,
you can use NVLink,

534
00:22:39.520 --> 00:22:41.500
you can use all these
fancy interconnects.

535
00:22:41.500 --> 00:22:43.750
They are growing, but they're
growing somewhat slowly.

536
00:22:43.750 --> 00:22:47.070
So this chart is like
normalized scaling bandwidth

537
00:22:47.070 --> 00:22:52.290
relative to when the first
generation of interconnects.

538
00:22:52.290 --> 00:22:56.320
The green line, this is
the global memory speed.

539
00:22:56.320 --> 00:22:59.080
So you go from GDDR to
HBM2E, and that's much,

540
00:22:59.080 --> 00:22:59.830
much faster right.

541
00:22:59.830 --> 00:23:00.580
This is log scale.

542
00:23:00.580 --> 00:23:02.100
It's 100x faster.

543
00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:04.270
But this is still
kind of slow scaling.

544
00:23:04.270 --> 00:23:07.870
And the gray line here,
this is compute scaling.

545
00:23:07.870 --> 00:23:09.970
This is the number of
floating point operations,

546
00:23:09.970 --> 00:23:11.940
if you're considering
the matmul FLOPs.

547
00:23:11.940 --> 00:23:15.100
This is how fast the
compute has been scaling.

548
00:23:15.100 --> 00:23:16.660
And this is astoundingly fast.

549
00:23:16.660 --> 00:23:20.280
It's 1 to 100,000 times faster.

550
00:23:20.280 --> 00:23:23.670
And so in the early days
of this scaling, maybe

551
00:23:23.670 --> 00:23:25.710
your problems were FLOPs based.

552
00:23:25.710 --> 00:23:27.960
You just didn't have enough
FLOPs to do your matrix

553
00:23:27.960 --> 00:23:28.960
multiplications.

554
00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:32.210
But now all the way to the
right with the A100s, these

555
00:23:32.210 --> 00:23:34.470
are astoundingly fast GPUs.

556
00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:37.490
Your bottlenecks are probably
going to end up being memory,

557
00:23:37.490 --> 00:23:39.290
because the memory is
not growing as fast.

558
00:23:39.290 --> 00:23:41.240
And as we go into
the future, this

559
00:23:41.240 --> 00:23:42.630
is not really going to change.

560
00:23:42.630 --> 00:23:43.797
DRAM is very hard to scale.

561
00:23:43.797 --> 00:23:46.130
You're going to keep getting
this bigger and bigger gap.

562
00:23:46.130 --> 00:23:48.705
So if you're ever designing
hardware efficient algorithms,

563
00:23:48.705 --> 00:23:51.080
you're going to have to think
more and more about memory.

564
00:23:51.080 --> 00:23:53.082
And so we're going to
keep a lookout on that.

565
00:23:53.082 --> 00:23:54.540
I'm going to keep
emphasizing this.

566
00:23:54.540 --> 00:23:57.920
It's one of the
important themes in GPUs.

567
00:23:57.920 --> 00:23:58.940
OK.

568
00:23:58.940 --> 00:24:02.690
So I've been kind of throwing
lots of GPU facts at you,

569
00:24:02.690 --> 00:24:05.280
especially if you haven't,
seen this recently.

570
00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:06.930
It may be kind of new.

571
00:24:06.930 --> 00:24:11.270
So just to recap, GPUs are these
massively parallel processing

572
00:24:11.270 --> 00:24:11.850
systems.

573
00:24:11.850 --> 00:24:13.850
They have same
instructions applied

574
00:24:13.850 --> 00:24:15.475
across many different threads.

575
00:24:15.475 --> 00:24:16.850
And they have
these things called

576
00:24:16.850 --> 00:24:19.880
SMs, which are kind of cores
that there's many, many of them

577
00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:21.530
in the GPUs.

578
00:24:21.530 --> 00:24:24.740
Compute and matrix multiplies
have scaled really fast,

579
00:24:24.740 --> 00:24:26.610
and they have scaled
faster than memory.

580
00:24:26.610 --> 00:24:28.810
And that is an important
part of the characteristics

581
00:24:28.810 --> 00:24:30.950
that you think
about, about GPUs.

582
00:24:30.950 --> 00:24:32.905
But there is some fast memory.

583
00:24:32.905 --> 00:24:34.280
It's not like
everything is slow,

584
00:24:34.280 --> 00:24:35.570
so there's nothing we can do.

585
00:24:35.570 --> 00:24:37.160
There's the memory hierarchy.

586
00:24:37.160 --> 00:24:39.410
So some kinds of memory
are very, very fast.

587
00:24:39.410 --> 00:24:41.120
Other kinds of
memories are slow.

588
00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:43.210
And so if we exploit
this hierarchy maybe

589
00:24:43.210 --> 00:24:45.230
we can get things that
are really, really fast.

590
00:24:45.230 --> 00:24:48.200
So that's things to
remember about the GPU.

591
00:24:48.200 --> 00:24:50.230
And if you remember
these facts, you're

592
00:24:50.230 --> 00:24:53.020
going to be able to think pretty
cleanly about the performance

593
00:24:53.020 --> 00:24:55.060
components that I'm
going to talk about next.

594
00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:57.195
Any questions before I
move on to the next part?

595
00:24:59.950 --> 00:25:00.785
OK, cool.

596
00:25:03.370 --> 00:25:07.390
So now you all are GPU experts,
and what we would like to do

597
00:25:07.390 --> 00:25:09.640
is we would like to make
machine learning workloads go

598
00:25:09.640 --> 00:25:12.550
very fast on a GPU.

599
00:25:12.550 --> 00:25:14.720
And so I'm going to
start with this chart.

600
00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:16.720
And one of our goals
will be to understand

601
00:25:16.720 --> 00:25:18.200
what this chart exactly is.

602
00:25:18.200 --> 00:25:21.400
I think it'll be a good
puzzle to get us motivated.

603
00:25:21.400 --> 00:25:24.640
And so here what we are
doing is we are multiplying

604
00:25:24.640 --> 00:25:26.120
square matrices together.

605
00:25:26.120 --> 00:25:29.850
So the x-axis is the size of
my square matrix multiplies.

606
00:25:29.850 --> 00:25:34.950
And the y-axis here, this is the
number of operations per second

607
00:25:34.950 --> 00:25:35.620
that I'm doing.

608
00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:38.100
So you can think of this
as hardware utilization

609
00:25:38.100 --> 00:25:40.290
on the y-axis.

610
00:25:40.290 --> 00:25:42.450
And so as I get bigger
and bigger matrices,

611
00:25:42.450 --> 00:25:44.850
I'm going to get better and
better hardware utilization

612
00:25:44.850 --> 00:25:47.680
because I have more work to do.

613
00:25:47.680 --> 00:25:51.690
So I don't-- that overwhelms
the overhead of launching jobs

614
00:25:51.690 --> 00:25:53.040
and things like this.

615
00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:55.470
But there's all these weird
things that are happening.

616
00:25:55.470 --> 00:25:58.990
You see 1, 2, 3 different,
4 different lines.

617
00:25:58.990 --> 00:26:02.490
And each of these lines
are kind of wavy in a way

618
00:26:02.490 --> 00:26:05.320
that's looks very unpredictable.

619
00:26:05.320 --> 00:26:08.130
And so we would like to
understand what exactly

620
00:26:08.130 --> 00:26:10.090
is going on with these lines.

621
00:26:10.090 --> 00:26:12.840
And by the end of this
section, my promise

622
00:26:12.840 --> 00:26:14.940
is that you will
understand exactly each one

623
00:26:14.940 --> 00:26:16.570
of these phenomena, and
you'll be able to say, yeah,

624
00:26:16.570 --> 00:26:18.070
that plot looks totally normal.

625
00:26:18.070 --> 00:26:21.750
That is a natural
thing for a GPU to do.

626
00:26:21.750 --> 00:26:26.010
So the very first part, is
if you look at that plot,

627
00:26:26.010 --> 00:26:28.320
you will notice that it
looks a little bit like this.

628
00:26:28.320 --> 00:26:31.130
And if you've taken a
systems hardware course,

629
00:26:31.130 --> 00:26:34.370
you should remember this as
kind of the roofline model.

630
00:26:34.370 --> 00:26:35.810
The roofline model
basically says

631
00:26:35.810 --> 00:26:40.490
if we're looking at throughput
or utilization, what we're going

632
00:26:40.490 --> 00:26:42.840
to find is there's two regimes.

633
00:26:42.840 --> 00:26:44.360
There's going to
be a regime that

634
00:26:44.360 --> 00:26:48.350
is memory limited, that is on
the left side of this curve

635
00:26:48.350 --> 00:26:49.540
on the green over here.

636
00:26:49.540 --> 00:26:51.290
And then there's a
part that is throughput

637
00:26:51.290 --> 00:26:52.640
limited on the right side.

638
00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:55.440
In some sense, you can think
of it as, on the right side,

639
00:26:55.440 --> 00:26:58.230
we are fully utilizing
our compute units.

640
00:26:58.230 --> 00:27:01.460
All the matrix multiply units
are multiplying all the time.

641
00:27:01.460 --> 00:27:03.740
And on the diagonal
here, we just

642
00:27:03.740 --> 00:27:05.880
have some sort of
memory bottleneck.

643
00:27:05.880 --> 00:27:08.960
And so our ability
to do computation

644
00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:12.980
is limited by the amount
of intensity that we have,

645
00:27:12.980 --> 00:27:14.790
the amount of FLOPs
per byte that we have.

646
00:27:14.790 --> 00:27:18.200
So we want to avoid being in
this left side region where

647
00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:19.050
we're memory bound.

648
00:27:19.050 --> 00:27:20.510
And we would like to
be on this right side

649
00:27:20.510 --> 00:27:21.968
where we're getting,
in some sense,

650
00:27:21.968 --> 00:27:24.490
full utilization of all
of our compute units.

651
00:27:24.490 --> 00:27:26.510
So that's, in some
sense, the goal.

652
00:27:26.510 --> 00:27:29.660
And hopefully this roofline
model looks something like this.

653
00:27:29.660 --> 00:27:31.305
We've got this diagonal part.

654
00:27:31.305 --> 00:27:32.680
And then we've
got this flat part

655
00:27:32.680 --> 00:27:33.890
all the way at the top here.

656
00:27:33.890 --> 00:27:38.500
So that's one part
of the mystery.

657
00:27:38.500 --> 00:27:42.940
And so this turns
out to be complex.

658
00:27:42.940 --> 00:27:45.280
The simple way to
say this is-- let's

659
00:27:45.280 --> 00:27:48.560
make sure that we're not
accessing memory unnecessarily.

660
00:27:48.560 --> 00:27:51.520
We have as few memory
accesses to slow global memory

661
00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:52.520
as possible.

662
00:27:52.520 --> 00:27:54.650
But it turns out that
in order to do that,

663
00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:57.130
we need a large array of tricks.

664
00:27:57.130 --> 00:27:58.540
There's a lot of
different things

665
00:27:58.540 --> 00:28:00.650
that you could do that
would mess you up,

666
00:28:00.650 --> 00:28:02.435
that would make you very slow.

667
00:28:02.435 --> 00:28:04.310
And the first one is
not a memory bottleneck.

668
00:28:04.310 --> 00:28:05.390
I'll just mention it.

669
00:28:05.390 --> 00:28:06.620
It doesn't come up too often.

670
00:28:06.620 --> 00:28:07.430
We'll get it out of the way.

671
00:28:07.430 --> 00:28:09.430
And then we'll talk
about the remaining five

672
00:28:09.430 --> 00:28:11.650
items that in some
sense are really

673
00:28:11.650 --> 00:28:16.510
core to thinking
about GPU performance.

674
00:28:16.510 --> 00:28:19.900
OK, so the first thing
that I want to talk about

675
00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:21.550
is conditionals.

676
00:28:21.550 --> 00:28:24.360
So as I said before, GPUs,
their execution model

677
00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:28.140
is something called SIMT,
Single Instruction Multi-Thread.

678
00:28:28.140 --> 00:28:30.630
And so every thread
in a warp is going

679
00:28:30.630 --> 00:28:33.300
to execute the same
instruction, and it's

680
00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:35.110
going to do so on
different data.

681
00:28:35.110 --> 00:28:37.925
And so what happens if
I write a piece of code

682
00:28:37.925 --> 00:28:38.800
that looks like this.

683
00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:39.910
I have an if statement.

684
00:28:39.910 --> 00:28:43.077
And if the thread index is
less than 4, do something.

685
00:28:43.077 --> 00:28:45.160
If the thread index is
greater than or equal to 4,

686
00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:46.118
then do something else.

687
00:28:46.118 --> 00:28:48.610
I have this very simple
conditional model.

688
00:28:48.610 --> 00:28:51.930
If I run this on the GPU,
what's going to happen

689
00:28:51.930 --> 00:28:56.940
is that I'm going to run
the A instruction on four

690
00:28:56.940 --> 00:28:57.910
of my threads.

691
00:28:57.910 --> 00:29:00.240
I will actually
pause my other four

692
00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:02.908
threads, which are supposed
to be executing the else part.

693
00:29:02.908 --> 00:29:04.950
And then these other four
threads will come alive

694
00:29:04.950 --> 00:29:06.190
and they will execute x.

695
00:29:06.190 --> 00:29:09.040
And these my original four
threads will go to sleep,

696
00:29:09.040 --> 00:29:10.680
and I will just
alternate executing

697
00:29:10.680 --> 00:29:12.070
each of these instructions.

698
00:29:12.070 --> 00:29:13.060
Why is that?

699
00:29:13.060 --> 00:29:16.615
I can't execute A and
x at the same time

700
00:29:16.615 --> 00:29:17.740
on these different threads.

701
00:29:17.740 --> 00:29:20.127
As I said again,
every thread has

702
00:29:20.127 --> 00:29:21.460
to execute the same instruction.

703
00:29:21.460 --> 00:29:24.360
So conditional statements
within a single warp

704
00:29:24.360 --> 00:29:26.640
can be really, really
damaging because they

705
00:29:26.640 --> 00:29:29.220
will force you to pause
any of the threads that

706
00:29:29.220 --> 00:29:36.270
are not doing exactly the
main control flow execution.

707
00:29:36.270 --> 00:29:38.610
OK, so that was the
only non-memory thing

708
00:29:38.610 --> 00:29:41.040
that I wanted to mention, and
it should be kind of obvious

709
00:29:41.040 --> 00:29:43.440
that you should probably
not be putting conditionals

710
00:29:43.440 --> 00:29:47.020
into your massively
parallel compute unit,

711
00:29:47.020 --> 00:29:48.940
but once we've gotten
that out of the way,

712
00:29:48.940 --> 00:29:50.730
the other tricks that
we need to consider

713
00:29:50.730 --> 00:29:53.220
are all kind of memory based.

714
00:29:53.220 --> 00:29:56.830
The first thing I want to
mention is lower precision.

715
00:29:56.830 --> 00:29:57.895
And this is a big trick.

716
00:29:57.895 --> 00:29:59.020
This is an important trick.

717
00:29:59.020 --> 00:30:00.840
You should do it all the time.

718
00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:04.800
There's kind of a-- going back
to this plot of Bill Dally,

719
00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:06.690
there's a sleight of hand here.

720
00:30:06.690 --> 00:30:10.020
This looks really good because
the numbers are going up

721
00:30:10.020 --> 00:30:10.810
and up and up.

722
00:30:10.810 --> 00:30:15.030
But if you look at what's
driving GPU progress over all

723
00:30:15.030 --> 00:30:17.670
these years, you
actually kind of see

724
00:30:17.670 --> 00:30:19.570
that it's number
representations.

725
00:30:19.570 --> 00:30:23.710
You go from FP32 to
FP16 to int8 to so on.

726
00:30:23.710 --> 00:30:25.770
You get many orders
of magnitude gains

727
00:30:25.770 --> 00:30:28.890
from just having lower and
lower precision in your GPU

728
00:30:28.890 --> 00:30:30.480
operations.

729
00:30:30.480 --> 00:30:33.700
And let me clarify why
that's so important.

730
00:30:33.700 --> 00:30:35.563
If you have fewer bits
in all of the things

731
00:30:35.563 --> 00:30:37.605
that you're computing and
your weights and so on,

732
00:30:37.605 --> 00:30:39.630
you have much
fewer bits to move.

733
00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:42.720
So even if you're accessing
these bits from global memory,

734
00:30:42.720 --> 00:30:45.420
they become much, much
less of a concern.

735
00:30:45.420 --> 00:30:47.710
So let's just give
a simple example.

736
00:30:47.710 --> 00:30:50.100
And let's just think
about arithmetic intensity

737
00:30:50.100 --> 00:30:52.070
of a simple
elementwise operation.

738
00:30:52.070 --> 00:30:53.320
So I'm going to do it in ReLU.

739
00:30:53.320 --> 00:30:55.780
So that's x equals max 0 and x.

740
00:30:55.780 --> 00:30:58.030
And I'm going to do that
on a vector of size n.

741
00:30:58.030 --> 00:31:01.090
Let's say naively I'm going
to do this on float 32.

742
00:31:01.090 --> 00:31:03.640
So how many memory
accesses do I have?

743
00:31:03.640 --> 00:31:05.080
I have to read my x.

744
00:31:05.080 --> 00:31:08.340
I have to write the result
of if x less than 0.

745
00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:10.180
And that's all in float 32.

746
00:31:10.180 --> 00:31:12.190
So that's kind of 8 bytes.

747
00:31:12.190 --> 00:31:13.750
And how many operations do I do?

748
00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:15.460
Well, I have to
do x less than 0.

749
00:31:15.460 --> 00:31:17.140
So that's one
comparison operation.

750
00:31:17.140 --> 00:31:18.460
And I do one FLOP.

751
00:31:18.460 --> 00:31:22.520
So I do 8 bytes per single
floating point operation.

752
00:31:22.520 --> 00:31:25.270
If I do this in
float 16 now, well, I

753
00:31:25.270 --> 00:31:27.170
haven't changed the
FLOPs intensity here,

754
00:31:27.170 --> 00:31:29.330
but I have the memory access.

755
00:31:29.330 --> 00:31:31.280
And so now I have
4 bytes per FLOP.

756
00:31:31.280 --> 00:31:34.400
In some sense I've gotten double
the memory bandwidth for free,

757
00:31:34.400 --> 00:31:37.990
assuming that I can
get away with FLOP 16.

758
00:31:37.990 --> 00:31:41.330
And this is a key part of how
a lot of things are designed.

759
00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:42.910
Part of the assignment
is going to be

760
00:31:42.910 --> 00:31:47.140
you're going to try and play
with various mixed precision

761
00:31:47.140 --> 00:31:51.460
or low precision training
and other kinds of things.

762
00:31:51.460 --> 00:31:54.160
And a key part here is
that not all the parts

763
00:31:54.160 --> 00:31:56.350
of your network and
your training algorithm

764
00:31:56.350 --> 00:31:57.940
should be put into
low precision.

765
00:31:57.940 --> 00:32:01.660
So let me give you an
example of matrix multiplies.

766
00:32:01.660 --> 00:32:04.490
So in matrix multiplies
that are mixed precision,

767
00:32:04.490 --> 00:32:07.670
what you would do is you would
have your inputs be 16-bit.

768
00:32:07.670 --> 00:32:09.700
So these are low precision.

769
00:32:09.700 --> 00:32:13.730
And then you're going to do your
multiplication in full 32-bit.

770
00:32:13.730 --> 00:32:16.450
And that's useful because
the intermediate computations

771
00:32:16.450 --> 00:32:18.430
as you're accumulating
partial sums,

772
00:32:18.430 --> 00:32:20.820
you would like that to
be in high precision.

773
00:32:20.820 --> 00:32:25.540
And so you're accumulating
this with FP32 accumulator.

774
00:32:25.540 --> 00:32:30.220
And then your tensor core
will return a FP32 result,

775
00:32:30.220 --> 00:32:34.360
which you can downcast if you
would like back into 16-bit.

776
00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:36.910
And so we have our
inputs in 16-bit.

777
00:32:36.910 --> 00:32:41.110
But things like the accumulation
we might want to do in 32.

778
00:32:41.110 --> 00:32:43.450
So there's lots of
different things.

779
00:32:43.450 --> 00:32:45.940
There's operations that
can use 16-bit storage.

780
00:32:45.940 --> 00:32:48.070
There's operations that
might need more precision.

781
00:32:48.070 --> 00:32:52.380
So you want to keep it
in either FP32 or FP16.

782
00:32:52.380 --> 00:32:54.270
You might want to have
operations that need

783
00:32:54.270 --> 00:32:56.050
more range, like exp functions.

784
00:32:56.050 --> 00:32:57.690
If you don't have
the dynamic range

785
00:32:57.690 --> 00:33:00.010
that might blow up or zero out.

786
00:33:00.010 --> 00:33:02.130
And so you might want
to put those in bf16.

787
00:33:02.130 --> 00:33:04.410
There's a lot of
careful engineering

788
00:33:04.410 --> 00:33:08.933
that has to happen in order to
make sure that these models are

789
00:33:08.933 --> 00:33:10.350
actually stable
when they're being

790
00:33:10.350 --> 00:33:11.830
trained with lower precision.

791
00:33:11.830 --> 00:33:13.650
But if you can do it,
that's really great

792
00:33:13.650 --> 00:33:15.608
because you've basically
doubled the throughput

793
00:33:15.608 --> 00:33:18.410
of your bottleneck
going from 32 to 16-bit,

794
00:33:18.410 --> 00:33:20.250
if your memory is
your bottleneck.

795
00:33:25.100 --> 00:33:27.890
The other one, and I think this
is kind of what a lot of people

796
00:33:27.890 --> 00:33:30.530
think of when they say I'm
going to write a CUDA kernel

797
00:33:30.530 --> 00:33:33.950
or something, operator
fusion is kind of both very

798
00:33:33.950 --> 00:33:37.980
intuitive and both like a fun,
natural one to think about.

799
00:33:37.980 --> 00:33:42.080
So one memory-- or sorry, one
mental model of how a GPU works

800
00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:43.880
and how memory
works is this kind

801
00:33:43.880 --> 00:33:47.360
of fun diagram of a
factory from Horus.

802
00:33:47.360 --> 00:33:49.430
So imagine you have a
factory, and your factory

803
00:33:49.430 --> 00:33:51.110
is your compute part.

804
00:33:51.110 --> 00:33:54.050
And so it takes in
little box widgets

805
00:33:54.050 --> 00:33:57.350
and then outputs little
triangle widgets.

806
00:33:57.350 --> 00:34:00.620
And if you grow your compute
but your belt conveyor that

807
00:34:00.620 --> 00:34:04.088
takes memory to compute
is finite bandwidth,

808
00:34:04.088 --> 00:34:06.380
you're not going to be able
to use your second factory.

809
00:34:06.380 --> 00:34:09.949
You're still capped by the speed
at which you can transfer things

810
00:34:09.949 --> 00:34:11.429
from memory to compute.

811
00:34:11.429 --> 00:34:13.738
And so you've got
this bottleneck.

812
00:34:13.738 --> 00:34:15.280
Now, of course you
already knew that.

813
00:34:15.280 --> 00:34:18.320
I've been hammering in the
memory bottleneck thing,

814
00:34:18.320 --> 00:34:20.110
but I think one
insidious way in which

815
00:34:20.110 --> 00:34:22.929
you can incur a ton of
overhead without really

816
00:34:22.929 --> 00:34:26.070
realizing it is this
left-hand-side computation

817
00:34:26.070 --> 00:34:26.570
pattern.

818
00:34:26.570 --> 00:34:31.130
So imagine the left side of this
plot is where the memory is.

819
00:34:31.130 --> 00:34:33.340
The right side is
your compute unit.

820
00:34:33.340 --> 00:34:35.480
And so to do computation
I start with a square.

821
00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:38.300
And I move my squares from
my memory to my compute.

822
00:34:38.300 --> 00:34:39.230
I do some operation.

823
00:34:39.230 --> 00:34:40.355
I turn them into triangles.

824
00:34:40.355 --> 00:34:42.710
Now I shift my triangles
back to memory.

825
00:34:42.710 --> 00:34:45.219
And then I realized I
need my triangles again.

826
00:34:45.219 --> 00:34:46.969
So I ship them back
into the compute unit.

827
00:34:46.969 --> 00:34:49.449
Now the triangles become
circles, and so on and so forth.

828
00:34:49.449 --> 00:34:52.489
I send my compute back and
forth and back and forth,

829
00:34:52.489 --> 00:34:53.420
back to memory.

830
00:34:53.420 --> 00:34:56.150
And you might call this
a very naive approach.

831
00:34:56.150 --> 00:34:59.458
And if you were just doing
operations naively on the GPU

832
00:34:59.458 --> 00:35:02.000
and just shipping the results
straight back to global memory,

833
00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:03.490
this is what you'd end up with.

834
00:35:03.490 --> 00:35:05.680
And if you count the number
of times a piece of data

835
00:35:05.680 --> 00:35:07.670
went back and forth,
this is pretty terrible.

836
00:35:07.670 --> 00:35:09.670
You've incurred tons
of memory overhead.

837
00:35:09.670 --> 00:35:11.890
Now, you should
be able to realize

838
00:35:11.890 --> 00:35:14.360
that if you look at the right
side, will this compute?

839
00:35:14.360 --> 00:35:15.970
Well, there's no
dependency, so I

840
00:35:15.970 --> 00:35:19.930
should be able to go square to
triangle to circle to rectangle

841
00:35:19.930 --> 00:35:21.107
and ship the rectangle back.

842
00:35:21.107 --> 00:35:23.690
I can just keep everything in
the compute unit the whole time.

843
00:35:23.690 --> 00:35:25.970
And that's the
right-hand-side diagram.

844
00:35:25.970 --> 00:35:28.190
And this is the mental
model of a fused kernel.

845
00:35:28.190 --> 00:35:29.710
You have a bunch
of operations that

846
00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:32.780
are going to happen on a
piece of data in sequence.

847
00:35:32.780 --> 00:35:35.593
Instead of writing it back into
storage, what I'm going to do

848
00:35:35.593 --> 00:35:37.510
is I'm going to do all
the computation as much

849
00:35:37.510 --> 00:35:39.670
as I can in one place,
and then only when I

850
00:35:39.670 --> 00:35:41.870
have to ship it back to memory.

851
00:35:41.870 --> 00:35:43.815
So that's this idea
of kernel fusion.

852
00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:50.590
There's some very
simple examples

853
00:35:50.590 --> 00:35:53.560
of how if you write
some naive code,

854
00:35:53.560 --> 00:35:56.390
you might get of a
naive set of launches.

855
00:35:56.390 --> 00:35:59.110
So here's an example
I wrote a little let's

856
00:35:59.110 --> 00:36:00.760
say neural network module.

857
00:36:00.760 --> 00:36:02.680
Let's say I write
a neural network

858
00:36:02.680 --> 00:36:06.190
module that takes in
x and it produces sine

859
00:36:06.190 --> 00:36:08.180
squared x and cosine squared x.

860
00:36:08.180 --> 00:36:09.500
Simple code.

861
00:36:09.500 --> 00:36:13.520
Now if I run this, the
computation graph in PyTorch

862
00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:15.090
is going to look
something like this.

863
00:36:15.090 --> 00:36:17.850
And it's going to launch a
whole bunch of CUDA kernels.

864
00:36:17.850 --> 00:36:19.700
It's going to launch
take in the x,

865
00:36:19.700 --> 00:36:22.860
and it'll launch a CUDA
kernel to compute sin x.

866
00:36:22.860 --> 00:36:24.710
It'll launch one to
compute cosine x then

867
00:36:24.710 --> 00:36:27.080
sine squared of x and
cosine squared of x and sine

868
00:36:27.080 --> 00:36:28.590
squared x plus
cosine squared of x.

869
00:36:28.590 --> 00:36:30.320
So there's a bunch
of back and forth

870
00:36:30.320 --> 00:36:32.610
that has to happen in order
to do this computation.

871
00:36:32.610 --> 00:36:38.000
It's exactly the left hand side
figure that I showed you before.

872
00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:41.000
But if you were a little
smarter and you either

873
00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:42.620
wrote your own CUDA
kernel or you use

874
00:36:42.620 --> 00:36:45.300
something like
torch compile, well,

875
00:36:45.300 --> 00:36:48.620
you can easily realize that
those five operations don't

876
00:36:48.620 --> 00:36:52.710
really depend on very much, they
use only a little bit of memory.

877
00:36:52.710 --> 00:36:55.280
And so you can fuse them
into a single operation that

878
00:36:55.280 --> 00:36:57.530
does everything on
GPU on a single thread

879
00:36:57.530 --> 00:36:59.670
without sending things
back to global memory.

880
00:36:59.670 --> 00:37:03.170
So really easy fusion
operations like this

881
00:37:03.170 --> 00:37:05.130
can be done automatically
by compilers.

882
00:37:05.130 --> 00:37:07.220
I just mentioned torch compiler.

883
00:37:07.220 --> 00:37:09.240
If you aren't already
doing this, you should.

884
00:37:09.240 --> 00:37:11.282
You should consider strongly
thinking about using

885
00:37:11.282 --> 00:37:12.600
torch compile everywhere.

886
00:37:12.600 --> 00:37:15.790
We'll show you in the assignment
torch compile as well.

887
00:37:15.790 --> 00:37:18.690
It's pretty nice.

888
00:37:18.690 --> 00:37:24.700
OK, so I've gone through
precision and fusion.

889
00:37:24.700 --> 00:37:26.820
If anyone has
questions, let me know

890
00:37:26.820 --> 00:37:29.130
before I move on
to recomputation

891
00:37:29.130 --> 00:37:33.360
and other kinds of tricks
that we can do on the GPU.

892
00:37:33.360 --> 00:37:35.340
OK, good.

893
00:37:35.340 --> 00:37:39.690
So another thing that we can
do is called recomputation.

894
00:37:39.690 --> 00:37:43.020
And recomputation is
this idea of spending

895
00:37:43.020 --> 00:37:46.870
more compute to avoid
having to do memory access.

896
00:37:46.870 --> 00:37:51.820
So remember your original
back propagation lecture.

897
00:37:51.820 --> 00:37:54.030
This one is actually from CS221.

898
00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:54.730
What do we do?

899
00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:56.950
Well, we take our inputs
at the very bottom.

900
00:37:56.950 --> 00:37:58.230
These are the yellow ones.

901
00:37:58.230 --> 00:38:00.550
And then we propagate
activations upwards.

902
00:38:00.550 --> 00:38:03.420
Those are also the yellow
values on the tree.

903
00:38:03.420 --> 00:38:05.500
And then we compute the
Jacobians backwards.

904
00:38:05.500 --> 00:38:07.630
Those are the green
values on the edges.

905
00:38:07.630 --> 00:38:10.100
And then to compute my gradients
I'm going to propagate.

906
00:38:10.100 --> 00:38:11.330
You multiply.

907
00:38:11.330 --> 00:38:13.780
So the Jacobian and
the activations I'm

908
00:38:13.780 --> 00:38:15.800
a propagate the
gradients backward.

909
00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:18.910
Well, if you think
about it, those yellow

910
00:38:18.910 --> 00:38:21.890
values after the forward
pass have to be stored.

911
00:38:21.890 --> 00:38:23.348
And then they're stored.

912
00:38:23.348 --> 00:38:25.390
And then they have to be
taken from global memory

913
00:38:25.390 --> 00:38:27.830
where I stored them and put
them into the compute units.

914
00:38:27.830 --> 00:38:30.520
Mechanically, that's
how it has to happen.

915
00:38:30.520 --> 00:38:34.510
But that might actually be a
ton of memory inputs and outputs

916
00:38:34.510 --> 00:38:35.890
happening.

917
00:38:35.890 --> 00:38:39.170
Instead you might actually
be able to avoid this.

918
00:38:39.170 --> 00:38:42.730
So let me give you an example of
how computation can speed things

919
00:38:42.730 --> 00:38:43.450
up.

920
00:38:43.450 --> 00:38:47.180
Here's another silly
function that I might write.

921
00:38:47.180 --> 00:38:49.978
I'm just going to stack three
sigmoids on top of each other.

922
00:38:49.978 --> 00:38:51.020
You can look at the left.

923
00:38:51.020 --> 00:38:52.450
That's the forward graph.

924
00:38:52.450 --> 00:38:55.630
That should be exactly your
mental model of three sigmoids

925
00:38:55.630 --> 00:38:57.040
on top of each other.

926
00:38:57.040 --> 00:38:59.473
Now the computation
graph for this,

927
00:38:59.473 --> 00:39:00.890
I'm going to compute
the sigmoids,

928
00:39:00.890 --> 00:39:02.830
and I'm going to
store S1 and S2, which

929
00:39:02.830 --> 00:39:04.400
are the activations
of the sigmoids.

930
00:39:04.400 --> 00:39:06.220
And I have my outputs.

931
00:39:06.220 --> 00:39:09.480
And then that's my forward pass.

932
00:39:09.480 --> 00:39:12.040
Now, the backward pass in
this is kind of terrible.

933
00:39:12.040 --> 00:39:16.110
When I do my backward graph, I
need to go and take S1 and S2,

934
00:39:16.110 --> 00:39:19.650
and I need to take the gradients
coming backwards into this

935
00:39:19.650 --> 00:39:23.590
out box and then push it into
this backwards computation.

936
00:39:23.590 --> 00:39:25.590
And I'll get the gradient of x.

937
00:39:25.590 --> 00:39:29.640
So I need to have three memory
reads one memory right in order

938
00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:30.970
to compute the backwards pass.

939
00:39:30.970 --> 00:39:33.870
And then for the forward pass I
need to do one memory read of x.

940
00:39:33.870 --> 00:39:37.510
And I need to do three memory
writes for S1, S2, and out.

941
00:39:37.510 --> 00:39:38.710
So hopefully that's clear.

942
00:39:38.710 --> 00:39:41.830
This is a decent amount of
memory reads and writes.

943
00:39:41.830 --> 00:39:43.063
I have to do eight of them.

944
00:39:43.063 --> 00:39:44.730
And I have very low
arithmetic intensity

945
00:39:44.730 --> 00:39:48.600
because I have no matrix
multiplies at all.

946
00:39:48.600 --> 00:39:51.240
So the idea of
recomputation is to say

947
00:39:51.240 --> 00:39:54.060
I don't want to store
those activations at all.

948
00:39:54.060 --> 00:39:55.750
I'm not going to put
them into memory.

949
00:39:55.750 --> 00:39:59.260
I'm just going to recompute them
on the fly in my backward pass.

950
00:39:59.260 --> 00:40:02.920
So now in my new forward
pass, I don't store S1 and S2.

951
00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:06.810
I take x as input, I compute my
sigmoids, and I get my output.

952
00:40:06.810 --> 00:40:11.210
So now that's one memory read
for x, one memory write for out.

953
00:40:11.210 --> 00:40:14.610
Now in my backward pass, I
don't have activations anymore.

954
00:40:14.610 --> 00:40:17.640
So what I'm going to do is
I'm going to get both D out,

955
00:40:17.640 --> 00:40:20.600
which is the backward
signal coming in from above.

956
00:40:20.600 --> 00:40:22.200
And then x which is my input.

957
00:40:22.200 --> 00:40:25.310
So I'm going to take two of
those, which is 2 memory reads.

958
00:40:25.310 --> 00:40:29.220
And then on the fly in
my SM in my local memory,

959
00:40:29.220 --> 00:40:31.247
I'm going to compute
each of these sigmoids,

960
00:40:31.247 --> 00:40:33.330
and I'm going to put them
into the backward graph.

961
00:40:33.330 --> 00:40:36.170
I'm going to recompute
S1, S2, and out

962
00:40:36.170 --> 00:40:38.870
on the fly inside
my local memory.

963
00:40:38.870 --> 00:40:41.180
And because I do that,
there's no global memory

964
00:40:41.180 --> 00:40:42.920
reads happening here.

965
00:40:42.920 --> 00:40:45.540
And then I have one
memory right which is dx.

966
00:40:45.540 --> 00:40:49.790
So now if you compare the two
I have 5/8 of the memory access

967
00:40:49.790 --> 00:40:51.510
for the exact same computation.

968
00:40:51.510 --> 00:40:53.360
The price that we
paid is that I'm

969
00:40:53.360 --> 00:40:55.740
going to have to recompute
these three sigmoids.

970
00:40:55.740 --> 00:40:57.950
But if you were
running idle anyway

971
00:40:57.950 --> 00:41:01.435
because you were memory capped,
this is a great trade off.

972
00:41:01.435 --> 00:41:02.810
You would be very
happy with this

973
00:41:02.810 --> 00:41:04.230
because now you've
traded compute,

974
00:41:04.230 --> 00:41:07.040
which you have too much of
for memory bandwidth, which

975
00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:08.180
you had too little of.

976
00:41:08.180 --> 00:41:10.890
So this is one
great way of trading

977
00:41:10.890 --> 00:41:15.740
one thing you need for
another thing that you have.

978
00:41:15.740 --> 00:41:17.460
And of course,
this is different.

979
00:41:17.460 --> 00:41:21.800
It's the same trick as gradient
checkpointing and recomputing

980
00:41:21.800 --> 00:41:23.835
activations for memory savings.

981
00:41:23.835 --> 00:41:25.710
But this is being done
for different reasons.

982
00:41:25.710 --> 00:41:28.933
This is for execution speed,
not just because you're

983
00:41:28.933 --> 00:41:29.850
running out of memory.

984
00:41:29.850 --> 00:41:32.185
So it's the same technique
but for different goals.

985
00:41:34.910 --> 00:41:38.780
And then this one
I think is actually

986
00:41:38.780 --> 00:41:41.000
kind of a really
interesting one, and not one

987
00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:42.620
that I knew until
I started really

988
00:41:42.620 --> 00:41:47.330
looking into how the hardware
model of a GPU and DRAM works.

989
00:41:47.330 --> 00:41:51.260
So the slow memory,
the global memory

990
00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:55.770
called DRAM in a GPU, that's
actually very, very slow.

991
00:41:55.770 --> 00:41:58.383
And in order to make
it faster, there

992
00:41:58.383 --> 00:42:00.050
are certain optimizations
that are being

993
00:42:00.050 --> 00:42:01.560
done at the hardware level.

994
00:42:01.560 --> 00:42:03.140
And one of the
optimizations that's

995
00:42:03.140 --> 00:42:05.340
done at a hardware
level for DRAM

996
00:42:05.340 --> 00:42:07.870
is that when you go and
read a piece of memory,

997
00:42:07.870 --> 00:42:10.300
you don't actually get
just that value back.

998
00:42:10.300 --> 00:42:13.480
You actually get a whole
chunk of the memory back.

999
00:42:13.480 --> 00:42:14.800
And this is called burst mode.

1000
00:42:14.800 --> 00:42:19.140
So let's say I went on and tried
to read the very first value

1001
00:42:19.140 --> 00:42:20.790
of this big memory block.

1002
00:42:20.790 --> 00:42:23.530
Instead of just the
memory giving me back a 0,

1003
00:42:23.530 --> 00:42:25.770
it would actually give
me back 0, 1, 2, 3.

1004
00:42:25.770 --> 00:42:27.520
It would give me back
four values at once.

1005
00:42:27.520 --> 00:42:28.770
It would be like, here you go.

1006
00:42:28.770 --> 00:42:31.830
I'm sure you'll need the 1,
2 and 3 too in the future.

1007
00:42:31.830 --> 00:42:33.990
And so each address
space is cut up

1008
00:42:33.990 --> 00:42:35.530
into what's called
burst sections.

1009
00:42:35.530 --> 00:42:38.250
And then you're given the
entire burst section rather

1010
00:42:38.250 --> 00:42:40.350
than just what you looked for.

1011
00:42:40.350 --> 00:42:42.330
And this might seem
very mystifying

1012
00:42:42.330 --> 00:42:47.100
why would the memory give you
three extra bytes for free when

1013
00:42:47.100 --> 00:42:48.930
you're just asking for one.

1014
00:42:48.930 --> 00:42:51.730
There's a very interesting
hardware reason,

1015
00:42:51.730 --> 00:42:54.210
which is that when you're
addressing into the memory,

1016
00:42:54.210 --> 00:42:56.590
in order to send the
signal out from the memory,

1017
00:42:56.590 --> 00:42:59.140
that those bytes have to
be moved to an amplifier,

1018
00:42:59.140 --> 00:43:00.097
that's the slow step.

1019
00:43:00.097 --> 00:43:01.930
And once you've done
that, you can get many,

1020
00:43:01.930 --> 00:43:03.210
many bytes bites for free.

1021
00:43:03.210 --> 00:43:05.730
And so that's why this
burst section thing exists.

1022
00:43:05.730 --> 00:43:08.390
It's kind of masking
this more expensive step

1023
00:43:08.390 --> 00:43:10.220
of actually moving
where the data is

1024
00:43:10.220 --> 00:43:13.730
stored to this amplifier.

1025
00:43:13.730 --> 00:43:16.490
But kind of regardless,
this kind of

1026
00:43:16.490 --> 00:43:19.310
means that we might be able
to significantly accelerate

1027
00:43:19.310 --> 00:43:22.920
our memory access if the pattern
of memory access is good.

1028
00:43:22.920 --> 00:43:27.570
So if I want to read this
entire block over here,

1029
00:43:27.570 --> 00:43:30.290
if I access it in
random order, then I'm

1030
00:43:30.290 --> 00:43:34.970
going to have to basically query
a number of times equal roughly

1031
00:43:34.970 --> 00:43:37.590
to the length of my query.

1032
00:43:37.590 --> 00:43:41.340
But if I go and I check
the very first value,

1033
00:43:41.340 --> 00:43:44.160
then I'm going to get all this
entire burst section at once.

1034
00:43:44.160 --> 00:43:45.660
And then if I go
and check number 4,

1035
00:43:45.660 --> 00:43:48.300
I'll get this burst section, the
second burst section at once.

1036
00:43:48.300 --> 00:43:52.340
And so I can basically get
four times the throughput

1037
00:43:52.340 --> 00:43:55.280
if I'm really clever
about my memory accesses

1038
00:43:55.280 --> 00:43:59.780
and only access just the bits
I need from each burst section.

1039
00:43:59.780 --> 00:44:01.970
So this is called
memory coalescing.

1040
00:44:01.970 --> 00:44:07.660
So if all the threads in a warp
fall within the same burst, then

1041
00:44:07.660 --> 00:44:10.672
basically the smart hardware
and programming model

1042
00:44:10.672 --> 00:44:12.130
will basically
group those queries.

1043
00:44:12.130 --> 00:44:15.500
Instead of querying 0, 1, 2,
3, it will group them and say,

1044
00:44:15.500 --> 00:44:17.170
just give me 0,
and then I will be

1045
00:44:17.170 --> 00:44:19.900
able to read out all
the 0, 1, 2, 3 at once

1046
00:44:19.900 --> 00:44:22.370
from this kind of
burst mode DRAM.

1047
00:44:22.370 --> 00:44:26.390
So remember that a warp
is 32 numbered threads.

1048
00:44:26.390 --> 00:44:29.240
And so memory accesses from
a warp happen together.

1049
00:44:29.240 --> 00:44:30.790
And so when these
warps are reading

1050
00:44:30.790 --> 00:44:32.690
in to these kind
of burst sections,

1051
00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:35.110
there's optimizations that
can be done so that you're

1052
00:44:35.110 --> 00:44:38.080
getting all 4 bytes at once
rather than getting one of them

1053
00:44:38.080 --> 00:44:39.170
at a time individually.

1054
00:44:39.170 --> 00:44:42.130
And so that will 4x the
throughput that you have

1055
00:44:42.130 --> 00:44:43.010
on your memory.

1056
00:44:43.010 --> 00:44:46.030
So these are very simple
things, but they're actually

1057
00:44:46.030 --> 00:44:46.730
very important.

1058
00:44:46.730 --> 00:44:50.300
Imagine I'm going to do
matrix multiplications, right?

1059
00:44:50.300 --> 00:44:52.820
This is a core thing that you're
going to have to do a ton.

1060
00:44:52.820 --> 00:44:56.140
If you were to implement, let's
say a neural network really

1061
00:44:56.140 --> 00:44:58.060
from scratch in CUDA.

1062
00:44:58.060 --> 00:45:00.210
In this case, imagine
I'm going to read

1063
00:45:00.210 --> 00:45:03.220
my matrices in one of two ways.

1064
00:45:03.220 --> 00:45:05.760
I can read it by
traversing the rows.

1065
00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:07.660
So each thread is going
to traverse the row.

1066
00:45:07.660 --> 00:45:11.260
Or I can read it
in column order.

1067
00:45:11.260 --> 00:45:13.480
So each thread is going
to go down a column.

1068
00:45:13.480 --> 00:45:16.710
Turns out that this
left one where you're

1069
00:45:16.710 --> 00:45:18.310
going across different rows.

1070
00:45:18.310 --> 00:45:21.070
So each thread is accessing
a different-- oh, sorry,

1071
00:45:21.070 --> 00:45:23.230
each thread is going
through columns.

1072
00:45:23.230 --> 00:45:26.730
This left model is
going to be quite slow

1073
00:45:26.730 --> 00:45:30.000
because the memory reads are
not going to be coalesced.

1074
00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:32.040
Whereas if you're going
to this right side

1075
00:45:32.040 --> 00:45:34.000
where each of the
threads are going down,

1076
00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:37.500
so they're incrementing in
rows, then these memory reads

1077
00:45:37.500 --> 00:45:39.090
will be coalesced.

1078
00:45:39.090 --> 00:45:42.182
And so you can think about it
for a moment why this is true.

1079
00:45:42.182 --> 00:45:44.140
When I first looked at
this diagram I was like,

1080
00:45:44.140 --> 00:45:44.920
isn't it reversed?

1081
00:45:44.920 --> 00:45:45.730
It's actually not.

1082
00:45:45.730 --> 00:45:48.000
This is the correct one.

1083
00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:51.390
And the way to think
about this is let's

1084
00:45:51.390 --> 00:45:54.870
say on this right-hand-side
diagram over here,

1085
00:45:54.870 --> 00:45:56.317
I'm going to have
a thread that's

1086
00:45:56.317 --> 00:45:57.900
trying to-- a series
of threads that's

1087
00:45:57.900 --> 00:46:00.190
trying to access left to right.

1088
00:46:00.190 --> 00:46:03.550
So each thread is going to try
to load the very first element.

1089
00:46:03.550 --> 00:46:06.480
And then in the next time
step I'm going to the load

1090
00:46:06.480 --> 00:46:09.998
the element from this column,
the second column and then

1091
00:46:09.998 --> 00:46:12.040
the third column and the
fourth column and so on.

1092
00:46:12.040 --> 00:46:15.340
So if that happens, what
happens at time step 1?

1093
00:46:15.340 --> 00:46:18.332
At time step 1, my first
thread loads at this point.

1094
00:46:18.332 --> 00:46:20.290
And then the second thread
loads at this point.

1095
00:46:20.290 --> 00:46:21.748
And then this point
and that point.

1096
00:46:21.748 --> 00:46:23.530
So those can't be
coalesced at all.

1097
00:46:23.530 --> 00:46:25.390
They're reading
different burst sections.

1098
00:46:25.390 --> 00:46:29.040
And so that means that I have to
read this entire chunk of memory

1099
00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:31.990
in order to perform
any an operation.

1100
00:46:31.990 --> 00:46:35.197
Instead, if I was going
in the column direction,

1101
00:46:35.197 --> 00:46:37.530
all the threads will be reading
within this single burst

1102
00:46:37.530 --> 00:46:39.750
section, and so
only one memory read

1103
00:46:39.750 --> 00:46:41.550
operation needs to
be performed, and you

1104
00:46:41.550 --> 00:46:43.050
get all of the memory at once.

1105
00:46:43.050 --> 00:46:45.040
This is a very low
level optimization,

1106
00:46:45.040 --> 00:46:46.200
but this is very important.

1107
00:46:46.200 --> 00:46:48.400
If your memory traversal
order is all wrong,

1108
00:46:48.400 --> 00:46:51.360
you will actually get much
slower memory accesses

1109
00:46:51.360 --> 00:46:53.280
than you really want.

1110
00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:55.430
OK.

1111
00:46:55.430 --> 00:47:00.890
So then that brings us to
the very last and big one.

1112
00:47:00.890 --> 00:47:03.950
And this is the idea of tiling.

1113
00:47:03.950 --> 00:47:07.560
And tiling is this idea that
you would like to group together

1114
00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:10.070
memory accesses in
order to minimize

1115
00:47:10.070 --> 00:47:13.550
the amount of global memory
access that we have to do.

1116
00:47:13.550 --> 00:47:15.890
And so to explain
this one, I'm going

1117
00:47:15.890 --> 00:47:19.110
to try to go through this
example of a matrix multiply.

1118
00:47:19.110 --> 00:47:22.040
And hopefully, I'll be
able to explain to you

1119
00:47:22.040 --> 00:47:25.550
why a naive algorithm
for doing matrix multiply

1120
00:47:25.550 --> 00:47:27.142
is going to be very problematic.

1121
00:47:27.142 --> 00:47:28.850
And then afterwards
I'm going to give you

1122
00:47:28.850 --> 00:47:31.080
a tiled version
of the same idea,

1123
00:47:31.080 --> 00:47:32.660
and hopefully you'll
be able to see

1124
00:47:32.660 --> 00:47:34.910
why that's going to reduce
the number of global memory

1125
00:47:34.910 --> 00:47:37.220
reads that you have to do.

1126
00:47:37.220 --> 00:47:41.120
So let's start with this
very simple matrix multiply

1127
00:47:41.120 --> 00:47:41.910
algorithm.

1128
00:47:41.910 --> 00:47:43.410
So I've got a matrix.

1129
00:47:43.410 --> 00:47:46.010
I've got this M matrix
on the left side.

1130
00:47:46.010 --> 00:47:48.860
I've got my N matrix on the top.

1131
00:47:48.860 --> 00:47:52.430
And in order to compute
the matrix product,

1132
00:47:52.430 --> 00:47:55.460
I'm going to have to
traverse over the rows of M

1133
00:47:55.460 --> 00:47:58.000
and the columns of N and
then take the inner product

1134
00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:00.470
and store that
into this P matrix.

1135
00:48:00.470 --> 00:48:02.170
Write the corresponding rows.

1136
00:48:02.170 --> 00:48:04.850
And I've written out
here each of the threads.

1137
00:48:04.850 --> 00:48:08.560
The thread 0
corresponding to where

1138
00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:11.530
they're storing their
outputs and the access

1139
00:48:11.530 --> 00:48:14.830
order in which they access each
of the individual elements.

1140
00:48:14.830 --> 00:48:18.130
Now notice here that
what's going to happen

1141
00:48:18.130 --> 00:48:20.410
is that the memory access
here is not coalesced.

1142
00:48:20.410 --> 00:48:24.040
Like, the row
matrices here, these

1143
00:48:24.040 --> 00:48:26.570
are going to be accessed
in a non-coalesced order.

1144
00:48:26.570 --> 00:48:29.540
And I have repeated
memory accesses.

1145
00:48:29.540 --> 00:48:33.820
So I've got M00 being accessed
in the first thread, M00

1146
00:48:33.820 --> 00:48:36.880
accessed here,
N10 being accessed

1147
00:48:36.880 --> 00:48:38.320
in two different threads.

1148
00:48:38.320 --> 00:48:43.000
So these values are being read
over and over from global memory

1149
00:48:43.000 --> 00:48:45.040
into many different threads.

1150
00:48:45.040 --> 00:48:48.340
So this is going to be
potentially very slow.

1151
00:48:48.340 --> 00:48:50.830
So there's a question
of can we avoid

1152
00:48:50.830 --> 00:48:54.160
having too many global
memory reads and writes what

1153
00:48:54.160 --> 00:48:55.690
I would ideally like to do.

1154
00:48:55.690 --> 00:48:58.410
So let me explain the
ideal outcome first,

1155
00:48:58.410 --> 00:49:00.100
and then I'll explain
the algorithm.

1156
00:49:00.100 --> 00:49:02.040
The ideal outcome
is that I would

1157
00:49:02.040 --> 00:49:07.140
like to spend one chunk
of time loading pieces

1158
00:49:07.140 --> 00:49:09.790
from global memory to shared
memory where things are fast.

1159
00:49:09.790 --> 00:49:12.250
I want to do a ton of
computation in shared memory,

1160
00:49:12.250 --> 00:49:15.420
and then I want to be done
with that piece of data.

1161
00:49:15.420 --> 00:49:16.660
That's the ideal outcome.

1162
00:49:16.660 --> 00:49:18.820
I've minimized my
global memory accesses.

1163
00:49:18.820 --> 00:49:22.943
So now how can I do in
this matrix multiply world?

1164
00:49:22.943 --> 00:49:24.360
So now what I'm
going to do is I'm

1165
00:49:24.360 --> 00:49:27.460
going to take my matrices, both
the M matrix and the N matrix.

1166
00:49:27.460 --> 00:49:29.470
And I'm going to cut
them up right into tiles.

1167
00:49:29.470 --> 00:49:32.020
So here I've cut this
up into 2 by 2 tiles.

1168
00:49:32.020 --> 00:49:35.260
So I've got a 2 by 2 m
tile and a 2 by 2n tile.

1169
00:49:35.260 --> 00:49:38.430
So I've got basically
smaller submatrices

1170
00:49:38.430 --> 00:49:39.880
within each of the matrix.

1171
00:49:39.880 --> 00:49:42.150
And now imagine that my
shared memory is big enough

1172
00:49:42.150 --> 00:49:45.000
to be able to fit these
submatrices within each

1173
00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:46.410
of these SMs.

1174
00:49:46.410 --> 00:49:49.980
So now this gives a very, very
simple algorithm with which

1175
00:49:49.980 --> 00:49:51.370
we can do computation.

1176
00:49:51.370 --> 00:49:55.340
So what I'm going to do is
I'm going to first load,

1177
00:49:55.340 --> 00:49:58.650
let's say this M00 tile
on the top left over here.

1178
00:49:58.650 --> 00:50:02.930
And I'm going to also load my
N00 tile into shared memory

1179
00:50:02.930 --> 00:50:03.630
here.

1180
00:50:03.630 --> 00:50:07.830
So now I have these partial
sums that I can compute.

1181
00:50:07.830 --> 00:50:14.190
I can take the row product
of M00, M01 with N00, N10.

1182
00:50:14.190 --> 00:50:16.320
And I can increment
that into P0.

1183
00:50:16.320 --> 00:50:19.070
I can do the same with all
of the different submatrices

1184
00:50:19.070 --> 00:50:20.790
that I can fill out over here.

1185
00:50:20.790 --> 00:50:25.590
Now then, once I'm completely
done processing these two tiles,

1186
00:50:25.590 --> 00:50:28.050
then I can load a
new tile over here.

1187
00:50:28.050 --> 00:50:30.650
And then I can repeat that
computation with my M tile

1188
00:50:30.650 --> 00:50:33.660
and my N 2.0 tile loaded
into shared memory.

1189
00:50:33.660 --> 00:50:36.260
And then I can increment
my partial sums in P.

1190
00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:39.410
So now I've really
consolidated and reduced

1191
00:50:39.410 --> 00:50:41.780
the amount of global
memory access I have to do.

1192
00:50:41.780 --> 00:50:45.660
I load as much memory as I can
at once into shared memory.

1193
00:50:45.660 --> 00:50:48.530
I do all of my
submatrix computations

1194
00:50:48.530 --> 00:50:50.100
on that tile that I can.

1195
00:50:50.100 --> 00:50:52.822
And then I move on
to the next one.

1196
00:50:52.822 --> 00:50:54.280
And of course, the
other nice thing

1197
00:50:54.280 --> 00:50:57.400
is that because I'm
loading an entire tile,

1198
00:50:57.400 --> 00:51:00.520
I can traverse these sub
matrices in whatever order

1199
00:51:00.520 --> 00:51:02.570
I want like column
major or row major.

1200
00:51:02.570 --> 00:51:04.780
And so I can coalesce all
of the memory accesses

1201
00:51:04.780 --> 00:51:07.580
whenever I'm loading a tile
from global to shared memory.

1202
00:51:07.580 --> 00:51:13.870
So there's wins all around
here when we tile our accesses.

1203
00:51:13.870 --> 00:51:17.440
So we can do a little
bit of tiling math.

1204
00:51:17.440 --> 00:51:21.622
So we've got let's say, a matrix
A, a matrix B, and a matrix C.

1205
00:51:21.622 --> 00:51:23.080
So let's say the
full matrix, these

1206
00:51:23.080 --> 00:51:25.190
are square matrices
are of size N.

1207
00:51:25.190 --> 00:51:28.790
And let's say I have a
tile of size T. Oh, yes.

1208
00:51:28.790 --> 00:51:29.830
Question.

1209
00:51:29.830 --> 00:51:35.470
Previous slide of
[INAUDIBLE] step three

1210
00:51:35.470 --> 00:51:39.067
we're loading and M00 again?

1211
00:51:39.067 --> 00:51:41.150
So in that case, I just
wrote it for completeness.

1212
00:51:41.150 --> 00:51:44.420
But M00 let's say is just
stored in the shared memory.

1213
00:51:44.420 --> 00:51:45.633
Let's just keep it cached.

1214
00:51:45.633 --> 00:51:46.550
I won't load it again.

1215
00:51:46.550 --> 00:51:49.580
Yeah, that's definitely
just there for completeness.

1216
00:51:49.580 --> 00:51:53.090
Not that you would actually
discard and reload the matrix

1217
00:51:53.090 --> 00:51:53.590
again.

1218
00:51:53.590 --> 00:51:55.890
That would be kind of insane.

1219
00:51:55.890 --> 00:51:56.910
Cool.

1220
00:51:56.910 --> 00:51:58.350
OK.

1221
00:51:58.350 --> 00:52:01.020
And so we can do very
simple tiling math

1222
00:52:01.020 --> 00:52:02.830
to think about what's happening.

1223
00:52:02.830 --> 00:52:06.570
So let's say I'm going to do an
N by N matrix multiply right.

1224
00:52:06.570 --> 00:52:09.010
So if I do a non-tiled
matrix multiply,

1225
00:52:09.010 --> 00:52:11.850
if I'm just going over rows
and columns, then every input

1226
00:52:11.850 --> 00:52:12.910
every time I process.

1227
00:52:12.910 --> 00:52:14.410
It has to come
from global memory.

1228
00:52:14.410 --> 00:52:17.790
So each input is read N
times from global memory.

1229
00:52:17.790 --> 00:52:21.150
So each of these
is read N times.

1230
00:52:21.150 --> 00:52:25.860
If I do a tiled matrix
multiply, well, the global reads

1231
00:52:25.860 --> 00:52:27.070
are operating over tile.

1232
00:52:27.070 --> 00:52:30.910
So I'm reading each input N
over T times from global memory.

1233
00:52:30.910 --> 00:52:33.190
And I'm reading T
times within each tile.

1234
00:52:33.190 --> 00:52:35.680
Of course, I'm doing
matrix, matrix multiplies.

1235
00:52:35.680 --> 00:52:37.745
So I can't reduce the
total number of reads.

1236
00:52:37.745 --> 00:52:39.370
I have to read all
the matrix elements,

1237
00:52:39.370 --> 00:52:44.160
but I can shift the reads into
basically fast shared memory.

1238
00:52:44.160 --> 00:52:48.540
So I do T times memory reads
into shared memory and N over T

1239
00:52:48.540 --> 00:52:49.960
times from global memory.

1240
00:52:49.960 --> 00:52:52.460
And that's great because if we
have a big shared memory that

1241
00:52:52.460 --> 00:52:55.460
can store big tiles, that's
a factor of T reduction

1242
00:52:55.460 --> 00:52:58.670
in the total amount of data that
has to come from global memory.

1243
00:52:58.670 --> 00:53:02.000
So tiling can be really,
really powerful of an idea

1244
00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:03.660
when you're operating
over matrices.

1245
00:53:03.660 --> 00:53:07.610
And you can move things
into shared memory.

1246
00:53:07.610 --> 00:53:10.160
Tiling is quite complex.

1247
00:53:10.160 --> 00:53:13.940
This is the source of
many, many confusing things

1248
00:53:13.940 --> 00:53:17.660
about GPU and matrix
multiply performance.

1249
00:53:17.660 --> 00:53:19.550
One thing that can happen.

1250
00:53:19.550 --> 00:53:22.100
Once we start tiling things,
you start asking things

1251
00:53:22.100 --> 00:53:24.410
about discretization.

1252
00:53:24.410 --> 00:53:26.970
So imagine I have
a tile size of 128.

1253
00:53:26.970 --> 00:53:30.500
That seems like a nice
good round tile size.

1254
00:53:30.500 --> 00:53:34.588
But then when I have a
full matrix of 256 size,

1255
00:53:34.588 --> 00:53:35.130
that's great.

1256
00:53:35.130 --> 00:53:38.060
That's a 2 by 2 tile,
things load nicely.

1257
00:53:38.060 --> 00:53:43.080
Now let's say I have a 257
size tile on the column side,

1258
00:53:43.080 --> 00:53:47.300
now this is a bad time because I
need to have six tiles in order

1259
00:53:47.300 --> 00:53:50.210
to cover this matrix, and
the two tiles on the right

1260
00:53:50.210 --> 00:53:51.930
are very, very sparse.

1261
00:53:51.930 --> 00:53:53.810
There's just not
much stuff in there.

1262
00:53:53.810 --> 00:53:56.630
And the problem with
this is that each tile is

1263
00:53:56.630 --> 00:53:59.340
going to be assigned to an SM.

1264
00:53:59.340 --> 00:54:02.640
So each of these tiles
is going to be a block.

1265
00:54:02.640 --> 00:54:05.130
And each thread is going to
be operating within each tile.

1266
00:54:05.130 --> 00:54:07.225
So those two tiles
on the right, they're

1267
00:54:07.225 --> 00:54:08.850
not going to be doing
very much at all.

1268
00:54:08.850 --> 00:54:11.215
Those SMs are going to be
basically be sitting idle.

1269
00:54:11.215 --> 00:54:12.840
And if you were kind
of compute capped,

1270
00:54:12.840 --> 00:54:14.798
you would have wanted to
more evenly distribute

1271
00:54:14.798 --> 00:54:16.590
the load between SMs.

1272
00:54:16.590 --> 00:54:20.270
So you have to basically
optimize your tile sizes

1273
00:54:20.270 --> 00:54:22.410
to try to avoid these
kinds of scenarios.

1274
00:54:22.410 --> 00:54:25.460
But in reality, there's
a lot of complex things

1275
00:54:25.460 --> 00:54:27.980
that go into setting
the tile size.

1276
00:54:27.980 --> 00:54:30.150
Remember, you have to
coalesce your memory accesses.

1277
00:54:30.150 --> 00:54:31.900
So you have to think
carefully about that.

1278
00:54:31.900 --> 00:54:36.000
You have to not exceed
your shared memory size.

1279
00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:37.830
So the tiles can't be too big.

1280
00:54:37.830 --> 00:54:40.550
And you have to divide the
matrix dimension, hopefully

1281
00:54:40.550 --> 00:54:42.720
evenly or as close to
evenly as possible.

1282
00:54:42.720 --> 00:54:46.692
So you don't end up with this
situation of an underutilized SM

1283
00:54:46.692 --> 00:54:49.750
the very end here.

1284
00:54:49.750 --> 00:54:50.600
Yes.

1285
00:54:50.600 --> 00:54:55.780
So if you had, say,
smaller sizes [INAUDIBLE]

1286
00:54:55.780 --> 00:54:58.300
would GPUs do something like
prefetching, where they can

1287
00:54:58.300 --> 00:55:01.970
fetch the next tile beforehand?

1288
00:55:01.970 --> 00:55:07.090
And so would that
happen [INAUDIBLE]?

1289
00:55:07.090 --> 00:55:07.600
Yeah.

1290
00:55:07.600 --> 00:55:09.790
So you're asking
about whether or not

1291
00:55:09.790 --> 00:55:13.700
you can overlap memory
reads and computation?

1292
00:55:13.700 --> 00:55:17.090
And yeah, that's
naturally done in GPUs.

1293
00:55:17.090 --> 00:55:20.240
They're always like trying to
use the available bandwidth.

1294
00:55:20.240 --> 00:55:21.920
As long as shared
memory is available,

1295
00:55:21.920 --> 00:55:23.660
they can go and
put things into it.

1296
00:55:23.660 --> 00:55:26.050
The issue is that whenever
you're effectively

1297
00:55:26.050 --> 00:55:29.500
utilizing your SMS,
you're basically maxed out

1298
00:55:29.500 --> 00:55:30.550
on your shared memory.

1299
00:55:30.550 --> 00:55:33.190
That's like the
bottleneck resource.

1300
00:55:33.190 --> 00:55:38.090
And so there is no place
to prefetch in some sense.

1301
00:55:38.090 --> 00:55:38.590
Cool.

1302
00:55:38.590 --> 00:55:41.350
OK.

1303
00:55:41.350 --> 00:55:43.850
And the other
thing that is very,

1304
00:55:43.850 --> 00:55:47.880
very, we're getting into
the weeds here, complex

1305
00:55:47.880 --> 00:55:53.310
is the interaction between
tiling and burst sections.

1306
00:55:53.310 --> 00:55:57.120
So imagine I have a
matrix layout that's

1307
00:55:57.120 --> 00:56:01.800
this, where I have my
nice burst sections,

1308
00:56:01.800 --> 00:56:04.630
and each burst section
lines up nicely with a tile.

1309
00:56:04.630 --> 00:56:06.690
So to read this tile,
all I have to do

1310
00:56:06.690 --> 00:56:09.580
