burst sections.

1321
00:56:35.890 --> 00:56:37.650
And so I have to do
two reads in order

1322
00:56:37.650 --> 00:56:40.180
to get this second row
and so on and so forth.

1323
00:56:40.180 --> 00:56:44.420
So I've essentially doubled
the number of memory accesses

1324
00:56:44.420 --> 00:56:47.510
because I've added a single
extra element at the very end

1325
00:56:47.510 --> 00:56:50.540
there that's kind of bumped
up the alignment of my burst

1326
00:56:50.540 --> 00:56:52.800
section and my align layout.

1327
00:56:52.800 --> 00:56:55.550
And so basically, if
tiles or your matrix sizes

1328
00:56:55.550 --> 00:56:57.510
aren't multiples of
your burst section,

1329
00:56:57.510 --> 00:56:59.930
you can easily end up
with situations like this

1330
00:56:59.930 --> 00:57:02.880
where the rows don't line
up with the burst section,

1331
00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:05.060
and you've doubled the
amount of memory access

1332
00:57:05.060 --> 00:57:06.470
that you have to do.

1333
00:57:06.470 --> 00:57:08.150
And the way to
get around this is

1334
00:57:08.150 --> 00:57:12.080
you have to do padding to be
able to get nice round matrix

1335
00:57:12.080 --> 00:57:14.600
sizes so that your
burst sections line up

1336
00:57:14.600 --> 00:57:16.490
with the size of your tiles.

1337
00:57:16.490 --> 00:57:19.005
So this is getting very
into the weeds here.

1338
00:57:19.005 --> 00:57:21.380
But if you really want to
squeeze out all the performance

1339
00:57:21.380 --> 00:57:23.150
from your matrix
multiplies, these

1340
00:57:23.150 --> 00:57:25.230
