utilization, you're

1458
01:02:49.110 --> 01:02:50.700
going to execute
the remaining 12

1459
01:02:50.700 --> 01:02:51.992
and wait for those to complete.

1460
01:02:51.992 --> 01:02:53.408
And that's going
to be really bad.

1461
01:02:53.408 --> 01:02:54.910
So if you look at
your utilization,

1462
01:02:54.910 --> 01:02:56.350
you've got good
utilization for a while.

1463
01:02:56.350 --> 01:02:59.010
You'll drop off a cliff, and
then you'll finish up your job.

1464
01:02:59.010 --> 01:03:01.980
So this is something
called wave quantization.

1465
01:03:01.980 --> 01:03:05.370
And so ideally your tile
sizes are either much bigger

1466
01:03:05.370 --> 01:03:08.550
than the number of
SMS or they're not

1467
01:03:08.550 --> 01:03:10.530
this where you're just
like barely over the SMS

1468
01:03:10.530 --> 01:03:15.270
and you've caused this
quantization error additionally.

1469
01:03:15.270 --> 01:03:16.830
Cool.

1470
01:03:16.830 --> 01:03:17.680
All right.

1471
01:03:17.680 --> 01:03:20.970
I know this is low level
details, but in many ways,

1472
01:03:20.970 --> 01:03:23.520
I've been saying
through many classes

1473
01:03:23.520 --> 01:03:26.880
that language models and deep
learning is attention to detail.

1474
01:03:26.880 --> 01:03:28.530
And these kinds of
attention to detail

1475
01:03:28.530 --> 01:03:31.170
is the things that allow
people to scale up LLMs

1476
01:03:31.170 --> 01:03:33.622
to really, really large sizes
and get great performance.

1477
01:03:33.622 --> 01:03:35.330
So it's worth knowing,
even if you're not

1478
01:03:35.330 --> 01:03:37.330
a person that's going to
do systems engineering.

1479
01:03:37.330 --> 01:03:39.770
So what were the tricks right.

1480
01:03:39.770 --> 01:03:41.190
Key ideas here.

1481
01:03:41.190 --> 01:03:45.300
First one is you got to reduce
the amount of memory accesses.

1482
01:03:45.300 --> 01:03:47.100
So there's lots
of ways to do it.

1483
01:03:47.100 --> 01:03:49.520
You can do coalescing,
so that you're not--

1484
01:03:49.520 --> 01:03:52.580
you can reuse reads that
you're getting for free.

1485
01:03:52.580 --> 01:03:54.620
You can do fusion
so that you can

1486
01:03:54.620 --> 01:03:56.840
fuse multiple
operations together

1487
01:03:56.840 --> 01:03:59.900
and avoid unnecessary
reads and writes.

1488
01:03:59.900 --> 01:04:01.740
You can move memory
to shared memory.

1489
01:04:01.740 --> 01:04:03.720
So even if you're
going to do reads,

1490
01:04:03.720 --> 01:04:05.780
they're going to be
from much faster memory.

1491
01:04:05.780 --> 01:04:08.660
And that's going to be tiling
tricks that you can do.

1492
01:04:08.660 --> 01:04:11.960
And then finally, you can trade
memory for other resources

1493
01:04:11.960 --> 01:04:12.837
that you do have.

1494
01:04:12.837 --> 01:04:14.420
So you can trade it
for compute, which

1495
01:04:14.420 --> 01:04:17.040
is going to be recomputation.

1496
01:04:17.040 --> 01:04:19.040
Or you can trade it for
just numerical precision

1497
01:04:19.040 --> 01:04:21.040
or stability, which is
going to be quantization.

1498
01:04:21.040 --> 01:04:22.580
So there's lots
of bags of tricks

1499
01:04:22.580 --> 01:04:26.400
that you have in order
to get performance out.

1500
01:04:26.400 --> 01:04:28.790
So there's lots of
things you can do.

1501
01:04:28.790 --> 01:04:31.250
You just have to be
really mindful of the role

1502
01:04:31.250 --> 01:04:33.940
that memory plays in the
performance of a GPU.

1503
01:04:33.940 --> 01:04:38.350
That's kind of the key
thing to get the most out.

1504
01:04:38.350 --> 01:04:39.230
Cool.

1505
01:04:39.230 --> 01:04:42.040
Any questions on that before
I move to the final part

1506
01:04:42.040 --> 01:04:44.980
with flash attention?

1507
01:04:44.980 --> 01:04:46.420
OK, good.

1508
01:04:46.420 --> 01:04:47.150
All right.

1509
01:04:47.150 --> 01:04:49.520
So now I'm going to
put it all together.

1510
01:04:49.520 --> 01:04:52.570
I'm going to try to make it
so that all the tricks that I

1511
01:04:52.570 --> 01:04:55.850
taught you aren't these random
disconnected facts about GPUs.

1512
01:04:55.850 --> 01:04:58.510
They're kind part of
the standard performance

1513
01:04:58.510 --> 01:04:59.870
optimization toolkit.

1514
01:04:59.870 --> 01:05:02.170
And flash attention
and flash attention two

1515
01:05:02.170 --> 01:05:04.450
will hopefully teach you
how that all comes together

1516
01:05:04.450 --> 01:05:07.070
to build one of the
foundations, I guess,

1517
01:05:07.070 --> 01:05:09.850
of modern high
performance transformers.

1518
01:05:09.850 --> 01:05:13.120
So flash attention, we
know that it dramatically

1519
01:05:13.120 --> 01:05:14.623
accelerates attention.

1520
01:05:14.623 --> 01:05:16.540
And most of you probably
know that that's done

1521
01:05:16.540 --> 01:05:18.730
through some CUDA kernel magic.

1522
01:05:18.730 --> 01:05:20.950
But maybe you don't
know all the details.

1523
01:05:20.950 --> 01:05:24.580
So what the paper says
is, OK, so there's

1524
01:05:24.580 --> 01:05:27.100
one part that's happening,
which is do attention

1525
01:05:27.100 --> 01:05:30.903
on a unoptimized PyTorch
transformer implementation.

1526
01:05:30.903 --> 01:05:32.820
If you fuse the kernel
and you do some things,

1527
01:05:32.820 --> 01:05:37.977
you can get significant speed
ups. And from the paper,

1528
01:05:37.977 --> 01:05:39.810
they say we apply two
established techniques

1529
01:05:39.810 --> 01:05:42.352
tiling and recomputation, to
overcome the technical challenge

1530
01:05:42.352 --> 01:05:45.880
of computing exact attention
and subquadratic HBM accesses.

1531
01:05:45.880 --> 01:05:48.487
So it's not
subquadratic computation

1532
01:05:48.487 --> 01:05:49.570
because you can't do that.

1533
01:05:49.570 --> 01:05:52.000
You have to compute
attention in general,

1534
01:05:52.000 --> 01:05:54.210
but they're going to get
subquadratic accesses

1535
01:05:54.210 --> 01:05:57.280
to the high bandwidth
or global memory.

1536
01:05:57.280 --> 01:05:58.510
And so that's really the key.

1537
01:05:58.510 --> 01:06:00.390
If your memory is
the bottleneck,

1538
01:06:00.390 --> 01:06:02.350
you want to make
that not quadratic,

1539
01:06:02.350 --> 01:06:05.310
so that at least you can pay for
quadratic cost with your compute

1540
01:06:05.310 --> 01:06:08.910
rather than with your memory.

1541
01:06:08.910 --> 01:06:11.865
So just for a really
quick recap at this point,

1542
01:06:11.865 --> 01:06:13.740
you've implemented
attention many, many times

1543
01:06:13.740 --> 01:06:15.670
in many classes.

1544
01:06:15.670 --> 01:06:17.920
So it's going to be three
different matrix multiplies.

1545
01:06:17.920 --> 01:06:21.840
You've got a K, Q and V
with a softmax in between.

1546
01:06:21.840 --> 01:06:24.730
So the matrix multiplies
are pretty simple.

1547
01:06:24.730 --> 01:06:26.800
That can be done with tiling.

1548
01:06:26.800 --> 01:06:28.530
I've showed you
examples like that.

1549
01:06:28.530 --> 01:06:30.430
And what's different
about attention?

1550
01:06:30.430 --> 01:06:31.940
Well, there's this
softmax thing.

1551
01:06:31.940 --> 01:06:34.020
That's going to be
the real tricky bit.

1552
01:06:34.020 --> 01:06:36.380
And then once we can
deal with the softmax,

1553
01:06:36.380 --> 01:06:39.350
all of the matrix multiply
things I was talking about

1554
01:06:39.350 --> 01:06:41.210
will just come into play.

1555
01:06:41.210 --> 01:06:44.190
So the matrix multiply,
as I said before,

1556
01:06:44.190 --> 01:06:45.780
is exactly what I taught you.

1557
01:06:45.780 --> 01:06:48.810
So if you look at the figure 1
from the FlashAttention paper,

1558
01:06:48.810 --> 01:06:51.450
this is really just a simple
tiled matrix multiply.

1559
01:06:51.450 --> 01:06:55.140
You see the K
matrix, the Q matrix,

1560
01:06:55.140 --> 01:06:57.210
you see it cut up
into small blocks.

1561
01:06:57.210 --> 01:07:00.210
Small blocks of it are
being copied to SRAM,

1562
01:07:00.210 --> 01:07:01.530
they're being multiplied.

1563
01:07:01.530 --> 01:07:04.080
And then they're
being accumulate--

1564
01:07:04.080 --> 01:07:07.640
they're sent to the HBM
where you do softmaxes

1565
01:07:07.640 --> 01:07:10.850
and then you multiply with a V.

1566
01:07:10.850 --> 01:07:12.830
So this is all
just really simple

1567
01:07:12.830 --> 01:07:15.090
in terms of the K,
Q, V matrix multiply.

1568
01:07:15.090 --> 01:07:17.670
But now we have to
think about the softmax.

1569
01:07:17.670 --> 01:07:20.000
What's going on
with the softmax?

1570
01:07:20.000 --> 01:07:22.350
So the key thing
here is the softmax--

1571
01:07:22.350 --> 01:07:24.480
sorry, I'm going to
roll back one step.

1572
01:07:24.480 --> 01:07:26.240
So the issue with
the softmax, what's

1573
01:07:26.240 --> 01:07:27.750
the problem with the softmax?

1574
01:07:27.750 --> 01:07:29.650
It's a global operation.

1575
01:07:29.650 --> 01:07:32.350
The softmax in an attention
operates row by row.

1576
01:07:32.350 --> 01:07:34.270
You have to sum the
entire row right

1577
01:07:34.270 --> 01:07:37.393
to compute the sum normalizing
term of the softmax.

1578
01:07:37.393 --> 01:07:38.560
And that's very problematic.

1579
01:07:38.560 --> 01:07:41.980
If I have tiles, ideally
I want to do everything

1580
01:07:41.980 --> 01:07:42.830
within the tiles.

1581
01:07:42.830 --> 01:07:45.890
I don't ever want to have to
write back to the big matrix.

1582
01:07:45.890 --> 01:07:49.150
And so I need a softmax
that can be computed

1583
01:07:49.150 --> 01:07:50.750
online within each tile.

1584
01:07:50.750 --> 01:07:54.580
I want to do as much computation
within each tile as possible.

1585
01:07:54.580 --> 01:07:58.120
So the key thing
here is to use what's

1586
01:07:58.120 --> 01:08:00.610
called the online softmax.

1587
01:08:00.610 --> 01:08:01.580
And so what is that?

1588
01:08:01.580 --> 01:08:04.720
If you have a stream
of values, normally

1589
01:08:04.720 --> 01:08:07.780
the batch version of the
softmax, you take all of your x1

1590
01:08:07.780 --> 01:08:10.517
through x of and you would
exponentiate them, sum them,

1591
01:08:10.517 --> 01:08:11.600
and you would divide them.

1592
01:08:11.600 --> 01:08:13.640
That's what you would do
in your normal softmax.

1593
01:08:13.640 --> 01:08:16.160
And then you would maybe
compute the maximum value,

1594
01:08:16.160 --> 01:08:17.979
and you subtract
that in order to be

1595
01:08:17.979 --> 01:08:19.550
able to make this
numerically stable.

1596
01:08:19.550 --> 01:08:22.689
So this is the standard
numerically stable softmax

1597
01:08:22.689 --> 01:08:24.790
on the left side.

1598
01:08:24.790 --> 01:08:27.670
So the online softmax, I've
taken this from Mikailov

1599
01:08:27.670 --> 01:08:29.970
and Gimelshein in 2018.

1600
01:08:29.970 --> 01:08:33.689
Well, you can realize
that you can pull out

1601
01:08:33.689 --> 01:08:38.250
via telescoping some kind
of an argument, basically

1602
01:08:38.250 --> 01:08:43.770
the current running normalizer
term and the current top term

1603
01:08:43.770 --> 01:08:46.050
of e to the xi minus max of xk.

1604
01:08:46.050 --> 01:08:47.550
So what you're going
to do is you're

1605
01:08:47.550 --> 01:08:49.890
going to maintain your
current max that you've

1606
01:08:49.890 --> 01:08:54.040
seen over x1 through x of j,
which is my current iteration.

1607
01:08:54.040 --> 01:08:58.359
And then I'm also going to
maintain this correction term.

1608
01:08:58.359 --> 01:09:01.630
If my max updated, this is going
to basically correct my max.

1609
01:09:01.630 --> 01:09:04.720
And then I'm going to add
my new term over here.

1610
01:09:04.720 --> 01:09:09.120
So this d of j is going to
track online the top term

1611
01:09:09.120 --> 01:09:11.290
of this equation 2 over here.

1612
01:09:11.290 --> 01:09:16.680
And then at the end, I can also
then compute the normalizer

1613
01:09:16.680 --> 01:09:19.630
and then get the normalized
y of i that I want.

1614
01:09:19.630 --> 01:09:24.149
This d of v is itself the
normalization term that I need.

1615
01:09:24.149 --> 01:09:27.630
So the key thing here is
that this can be done online.

1616
01:09:27.630 --> 01:09:29.880
I don't need the x1
through x of n up front.

1617
01:09:29.880 --> 01:09:34.080
All I need is the
stream of x1 through xn.

1618
01:09:34.080 --> 01:09:36.740
And that's really key because
I can now compute the softmax

1619
01:09:36.740 --> 01:09:37.939
tile by tile.

1620
01:09:37.939 --> 01:09:40.319
Within each tile, can
run this algorithm,

1621
01:09:40.319 --> 01:09:44.069
and that will let me compute the
partial softmax for that tile.

1622
01:09:44.069 --> 01:09:47.779
And then I can write back if
I need to all the components

1623
01:09:47.779 --> 01:09:49.710
that I'm keeping track of.

1624
01:09:49.710 --> 01:09:52.319
And that's all that I need in
order to do this computation.

1625
01:09:52.319 --> 01:09:57.230
So I never have to materialize
the full n squared matrix

1626
01:09:57.230 --> 01:10:00.410
in order to compute the softmax.

1627
01:10:00.410 --> 01:10:03.380
And so that's basically it.

1628
01:10:03.380 --> 01:10:05.810
Once you have that,
you've put it all together

1629
01:10:05.810 --> 01:10:08.910
and you can get the forward
pass of flash attention.

1630
01:10:08.910 --> 01:10:11.730
And if you go and look at the
flash attention two paper,

1631
01:10:11.730 --> 01:10:13.520
which is going to be
a thing that we're

1632
01:10:13.520 --> 01:10:15.000
going to ask you to implement.

1633
01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:18.350
So you're going to be following
through these steps here.

1634
01:10:18.350 --> 01:10:20.700
You're going to see
exactly this idea.

1635
01:10:20.700 --> 01:10:23.910
So first, you're going to
have your KQ matrix multiply.

1636
01:10:23.910 --> 01:10:25.200
And this is going to be tiled.

1637
01:10:25.200 --> 01:10:26.600
So these are little tile chunks.

1638
01:10:26.600 --> 01:10:28.080
And they're going
to be multiplied.

1639
01:10:28.080 --> 01:10:29.830
And how am I going to
compute the softmax.

1640
01:10:29.830 --> 01:10:33.140
Well, I'm going to
maintain a running value

1641
01:10:33.140 --> 01:10:35.928
of these exponentiated sums.

1642
01:10:35.928 --> 01:10:37.970
And then I'm going to keep
incrementally updating

1643
01:10:37.970 --> 01:10:40.110
it and correcting for
the maximum terms.

1644
01:10:40.110 --> 01:10:43.910
And by doing that, I can compute
all of the necessary quantities

1645
01:10:43.910 --> 01:10:47.605
tile by tile going from
one tile to another,

1646
01:10:47.605 --> 01:10:48.980
and then just
multiply once again

1647
01:10:48.980 --> 01:10:51.510
with tiles with v in the end.

1648
01:10:51.510 --> 01:10:55.820
And that will give me
my full softmax output.

1649
01:10:55.820 --> 01:10:56.850
Yes.

1650
01:10:56.850 --> 01:11:02.420
So we won't be able to compute
that until we compute the QK

1651
01:11:02.420 --> 01:11:05.100
multiplication across
all of the tiles.

1652
01:11:05.100 --> 01:11:08.090
So we do have to double
back on each tile.

1653
01:11:08.090 --> 01:11:11.000
So the question was you
can't compute this until you

1654
01:11:11.000 --> 01:11:13.170
are done with all the tiles.

1655
01:11:13.170 --> 01:11:17.900
And so you have to double
back on all the tiles.

1656
01:11:17.900 --> 01:11:21.388
We'll talk about denominator
sum until we've seen every tile.

1657
01:11:21.388 --> 01:11:21.930
That's right.

1658
01:11:21.930 --> 01:11:24.790
So you will have to-- before
you can output your softmax,

1659
01:11:24.790 --> 01:11:26.540
you will have to go
through all the tiles.

1660
01:11:26.540 --> 01:11:31.000
This is correct, but let's
say I do all the tiles once.

1661
01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:32.783
I do all n square tiles.

1662
01:11:32.783 --> 01:11:34.450
At that point, I have
all the components

1663
01:11:34.450 --> 01:11:36.370
that I need in order
to directly output

1664
01:11:36.370 --> 01:11:37.640
the softmax at that point.

1665
01:11:37.640 --> 01:11:41.230
I don't have to do recomputation
because I have the normalizer

1666
01:11:41.230 --> 01:11:42.190
terms already.

1667
01:11:42.190 --> 01:11:44.510
By going through
each of these tiles,

1668
01:11:44.510 --> 01:11:46.970
at the end of going
through all these tiles,

1669
01:11:46.970 --> 01:11:50.290
I've built up L3
or L of n, which

1670
01:11:50.290 --> 01:11:52.880
is the sum of all of
the exponentiated terms.

1671
01:11:52.880 --> 01:11:55.750
So I already have
that in my shared

1672
01:11:55.750 --> 01:11:57.890
memory for this last tile.

1673
01:11:57.890 --> 01:12:00.760
And then that allows me
to exponentiate and divide

1674
01:12:00.760 --> 01:12:02.990
and then return all
of the components.

1675
01:12:07.408 --> 01:12:10.450
So the backward pass
I'm not going to cover.

1676
01:12:10.450 --> 01:12:12.620
You can do recomputation
tile by tile,

1677
01:12:12.620 --> 01:12:15.320
which will allow you to
avoid storing the softmax.

1678
01:12:15.320 --> 01:12:18.340
Remember, I always want
to avoid storing anything

1679
01:12:18.340 --> 01:12:19.850
that's of size n squared.

1680
01:12:19.850 --> 01:12:22.270
And so here I've been
clever with the tiles

1681
01:12:22.270 --> 01:12:25.440
so that I don't have to store
any of the n squared components

1682
01:12:25.440 --> 01:12:27.430
when I'm computing, for
example, the softmax.

1683
01:12:27.430 --> 01:12:30.190
But in the backwards pass,
if I store the activations,

1684
01:12:30.190 --> 01:12:32.400
that's already something
that's n squared size.

1685
01:12:32.400 --> 01:12:34.930
So I don't want to store
my n squared activations.

1686
01:12:34.930 --> 01:12:37.920
I'm going to have to recompute
it on the fly tile by tile

1687
01:12:37.920 --> 01:12:39.820
when I do the backwards pass.

1688
01:12:39.820 --> 01:12:41.520
So that's a really
key other trick

1689
01:12:41.520 --> 01:12:44.770
that they do in order to make
the backwards pass possible.

1690
01:12:44.770 --> 01:12:46.990
But otherwise, it's
fairly standard.

1691
01:12:46.990 --> 01:12:49.920
It's the same thing as computing
the gradients just tile by tile

1692
01:12:49.920 --> 01:12:51.460
and doing that computation.

1693
01:12:55.260 --> 01:12:58.200
So OK, that brings
us to the end here.

1694
01:12:58.200 --> 01:13:00.090
Hopefully you've seen
how all of the pieces

1695
01:13:00.090 --> 01:13:02.220
I talked about, about
tiling and coalescing

